WEBVTT

1
00:00:27,166 --> 00:00:29,166
(♪ Dua Lipa "End Of An Era" playing)

2
00:00:35,458 --> 00:00:37,041
♪ <i>One, two, three, ayy </i>♪

3
00:00:38,333 --> 00:00:40,500
♪ <i>What's it about a kiss </i>♪

4
00:00:40,583 --> 00:00:42,666
♪ <i>That makes me Feel like this?</i> ♪

5
00:00:42,750 --> 00:00:46,125
♪ <i>Makes me an optimist I guess </i>♪

6
00:00:46,666 --> 00:00:50,625
♪ <i>I always jump too quick</i>
<i>Hopin' this one might stick</i> ♪

7
00:00:50,708 --> 00:00:52,750
♪ <i>Hopelessly romantic</i> ♪

8
00:00:52,833 --> 00:00:56,375
♪ <i>Then you said "Hey"</i> ♪

9
00:00:56,458 --> 00:01:00,041
♪ <i>And I said "Hey"</i> ♪

10
00:01:00,708 --> 00:01:04,125
♪ <i>What's your name?</i> ♪

11
00:01:04,916 --> 00:01:06,416
♪ <i>Come with me</i> ♪

12
00:01:06,500 --> 00:01:07,875
- (horn honks)
- (gasps) Whoa!

13
00:01:07,958 --> 00:01:12,875
♪ <i>'Cause when I see your face Ah </i>♪

14
00:01:12,958 --> 00:01:16,416
♪ <i>The sweetest pleasure</i> ♪

15
00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:20,666
♪ <i>I feel like We're gonna be together</i> ♪

16
00:01:20,750 --> 00:01:24,666
♪ <i>This could be The end of an era</i> ♪

17
00:01:24,750 --> 00:01:28,416
♪ <i>Who knows, baby This could be forever</i> ♪

18
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:30,458
♪ <i>Forever</i> ♪

19
00:01:30,541 --> 00:01:32,375
♪ <i>In the clouds There she goes</i> ♪

20
00:01:32,458 --> 00:01:34,500
♪ <i>Butterflies Let them flow</i> ♪

21
00:01:34,583 --> 00:01:36,458
♪ <i>'Nother girl falls in love</i> ♪

22
00:01:36,541 --> 00:01:38,541
♪ <i>Another girl Leaves the club</i> ♪

23
00:01:41,166 --> 00:01:45,000
♪ <i>I've lost all my senses</i> ♪

24
00:01:45,083 --> 00:01:47,291
♪ <i>La-la-la-la La-la-la-la-la...</i> ♪

25
00:01:47,375 --> 00:01:49,500
(applause)

26
00:01:50,416 --> 00:01:51,500
Yeah!

27
00:01:52,583 --> 00:01:53,958
Ah! (chuckles)

28
00:01:59,750 --> 00:02:01,000
What?

29
00:02:01,083 --> 00:02:03,041
Two years in a row. Well done.

30
00:02:03,125 --> 00:02:05,750
Mmm. Yes, thank you. Alert the media.

31
00:02:06,250 --> 00:02:07,625
- Oh, wait. That's us.
- (chuckles)

32
00:02:07,708 --> 00:02:09,041
(announcer) And now we've arrived

33
00:02:09,125 --> 00:02:10,541
at the Golden Keyboard,

34
00:02:10,625 --> 00:02:12,666
for the story or series that constitutes

35
00:02:12,750 --> 00:02:15,916
outstanding enterprise
or investigative reporting.

36
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,458
Our first nominee,
from the <i>New York Vanguard</i> is

37
00:02:19,541 --> 00:02:20,541
Andy Sachs,

38
00:02:20,625 --> 00:02:23,708
for "Hearts of the City:
Stories of Resilience."

39
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:26,791
Our second nominee,
from the <i>Gotham Sentinel</i>

40
00:02:26,875 --> 00:02:29,083
is George Ali for "The Subway Tapes."

41
00:02:29,958 --> 00:02:30,958
From the <i>Borough Report,</i>

42
00:02:31,041 --> 00:02:33,791
Yvonne Simpson for, "The Cost
Of Medical Care is Terminal."

43
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:36,625
From the <i>New York Metro Constitution,</i>

44
00:02:36,708 --> 00:02:39,375
Daniel Goldbaum,
for "Fighting Fire with Fire."

45
00:02:39,458 --> 00:02:40,458
It's everybody.

46
00:02:43,375 --> 00:02:44,916
(announcer) And the winner is

47
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:46,000
Andy Sachs.

48
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:49,583
(cheering)

49
00:02:51,166 --> 00:02:52,166
Go.

50
00:02:52,750 --> 00:02:53,750
Go.

51
00:02:53,833 --> 00:02:54,833
(attendee) It's great!

52
00:02:54,916 --> 00:02:56,041
That's right, Andy!

53
00:03:04,916 --> 00:03:05,916
(sighs)

54
00:03:06,625 --> 00:03:09,208
Uh... (breathing shakily)

55
00:03:09,291 --> 00:03:11,583
Thank you for this award. Um...

56
00:03:11,666 --> 00:03:14,458
Sorry. I know I look, uh...
(inhales deeply)

57
00:03:14,541 --> 00:03:17,416
...shocked sad, instead of shocked happy,

58
00:03:17,958 --> 00:03:19,666
and, uh... (stammers)

59
00:03:20,541 --> 00:03:23,458
...that's because I...
I just... (inhales sharply)

60
00:03:23,541 --> 00:03:25,708
I and that whole table

61
00:03:25,791 --> 00:03:29,875
full of talented,
award-winning professionals

62
00:03:29,958 --> 00:03:32,000
from my paper, the <i>Vanguard</i>,

63
00:03:33,375 --> 00:03:34,375
just got fired...

64
00:03:34,458 --> 00:03:35,791
- What?
- (gasping)

65
00:03:35,875 --> 00:03:37,250
- ...by text.
- (gasping)

66
00:03:38,791 --> 00:03:44,166
We understand journalism is changing,

67
00:03:44,250 --> 00:03:46,166
but it's still devastating

68
00:03:46,250 --> 00:03:47,916
when something like this happens to you.

69
00:03:48,583 --> 00:03:51,833
Turns out our parent company is taking

70
00:03:51,916 --> 00:03:54,875
a 500-million-dollar write-down,

71
00:03:54,958 --> 00:03:57,625
so we're... (exhales deeply)

72
00:03:57,708 --> 00:04:00,166
...technical term, toast.

73
00:04:00,250 --> 00:04:01,833
(♪ Ledisi "Daydreaming" playing)

74
00:04:02,958 --> 00:04:05,333
(friend) I can't believe
they just fired everyone.

75
00:04:05,958 --> 00:04:08,000
At least it's a good picture of you.

76
00:04:08,083 --> 00:04:10,666
I just feel so terrible
for everyone at the paper.

77
00:04:11,583 --> 00:04:13,583
John's wife's about to have
their second baby.

78
00:04:13,666 --> 00:04:15,791
And Allison just bought a house.

79
00:04:16,666 --> 00:04:17,958
Also, it's so unfair.

80
00:04:18,041 --> 00:04:19,833
The CEO of the company that owns the paper

81
00:04:19,916 --> 00:04:22,041
just took home 11 million last year.

82
00:04:22,125 --> 00:04:23,083
Make that make sense.

83
00:04:23,625 --> 00:04:26,708
I can't. But you are gonna be okay.

84
00:04:27,208 --> 00:04:28,208
I don't know, Lil.

85
00:04:28,291 --> 00:04:30,125
Everyone I know is going through this.

86
00:04:30,208 --> 00:04:32,708
Layoffs, downsizing, consolidation.

87
00:04:32,791 --> 00:04:34,666
It's just brutal.

88
00:04:34,750 --> 00:04:36,750
(clicks tongue) Anyway...

89
00:04:38,083 --> 00:04:39,083
I know that I'm lucky.

90
00:04:39,166 --> 00:04:41,000
I know that a lot of people
have it worse than me.

91
00:04:41,083 --> 00:04:43,041
Most people have it worse
than me. It's just...

92
00:04:43,125 --> 00:04:44,291
I'll be fine. I'll be fine.

93
00:04:44,375 --> 00:04:46,250
It is so unfair.

94
00:04:46,333 --> 00:04:49,416
You've worked your ass off
for a whole two decades,

95
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:50,916
all across the country and the world,

96
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:52,833
and you never took the easy paycheck.

97
00:04:52,916 --> 00:04:55,166
- Never slept with a colleague.
- Mmm?

98
00:04:55,250 --> 00:04:57,875
- I mean, one.
- Mmm.

99
00:04:57,958 --> 00:04:59,166
Two.

100
00:04:59,250 --> 00:05:00,333
Anyway, the point is,

101
00:05:00,416 --> 00:05:02,416
is that I never slept with
anyone who could promote me,

102
00:05:02,500 --> 00:05:04,375
just the hot powerless ones.

103
00:05:04,958 --> 00:05:07,375
Are you sure you don't wanna

104
00:05:07,458 --> 00:05:09,291
come and work for me at the gallery?

105
00:05:10,125 --> 00:05:11,958
I need someone who can write decent copy.

106
00:05:12,041 --> 00:05:13,291
And you need a job.

107
00:05:13,375 --> 00:05:14,750
So sweet.

108
00:05:14,833 --> 00:05:16,625
No, thank you. Not yet.

109
00:05:16,708 --> 00:05:18,500
(♪ Miley Cyrus "Walk of Fame" playing)

110
00:05:18,583 --> 00:05:19,708
(horn honks)

111
00:05:20,416 --> 00:05:21,750
So what do I tell her?

112
00:05:23,125 --> 00:05:25,833
Okay. All right. (sighs) Hold on.

113
00:05:26,583 --> 00:05:28,916
You're sure the story
is not gonna break tonight?

114
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:30,875
PR says we have a day or two.

115
00:05:31,458 --> 00:05:33,416
Well, that's something.

116
00:05:33,500 --> 00:05:35,375
I won't tell her until tomorrow then.

117
00:05:35,458 --> 00:05:37,583
No point in spoiling the evening.

118
00:05:40,500 --> 00:05:41,666
(clamoring)

119
00:05:41,750 --> 00:05:46,000
(singer vocalizing)

120
00:05:46,083 --> 00:05:48,500
♪ <i>Every day</i> ♪

121
00:05:48,583 --> 00:05:51,541
♪ <i>Every night It's all the same </i>♪

122
00:05:54,375 --> 00:05:58,375
♪ <i>Hungry cries Are callin' out my name</i> ♪

123
00:06:00,875 --> 00:06:02,791
♪ <i>Walk away</i> ♪

124
00:06:05,541 --> 00:06:06,583
♪ <i>Yeah</i> ♪

125
00:06:09,583 --> 00:06:13,041
♪ <i>Every time I walk It's a walk of fame</i> ♪

126
00:06:13,125 --> 00:06:16,625
♪ <i>And the cars are bright</i>
<i>And lightin' up my face</i> ♪

127
00:06:18,500 --> 00:06:20,708
- (paparazza 1) It's Miranda.
- (paparazza 2) Is it Miranda?

128
00:06:22,458 --> 00:06:23,875
- Miranda!
- Miranda!

129
00:06:24,375 --> 00:06:27,625
♪ <i>Ooh yeah It's a walk of fame</i> ♪

130
00:06:27,708 --> 00:06:31,833
♪ <i>And through the tears</i>
<i>I can see it so clear</i> ♪

131
00:06:32,625 --> 00:06:33,833
Miranda!

132
00:06:33,916 --> 00:06:35,291
Miranda!

133
00:06:35,375 --> 00:06:36,208
♪ ...<i>walk away </i>♪

134
00:06:36,291 --> 00:06:38,000
♪ <i>Yeah, every time I walk</i> ♪

135
00:06:38,083 --> 00:06:39,375
♪ <i>It's a walk of fame</i> ♪

136
00:06:39,458 --> 00:06:42,583
♪ <i>Ooh yeah It's a walk of fame</i> ♪

137
00:06:42,666 --> 00:06:45,333
♪ <i>And through the mirror...</i> ♪

138
00:06:50,708 --> 00:06:52,375
(journalist) Is <i>Runway</i> responsible?

139
00:06:52,458 --> 00:06:54,375
- (journalists shouting)
- (gasps)

140
00:06:54,458 --> 00:06:55,583
(Amari) Not tonight.

141
00:06:56,666 --> 00:06:59,041
Hi. I just wanted to tell you that

142
00:06:59,125 --> 00:07:00,875
the story broke online...

143
00:07:00,958 --> 00:07:02,250
(Miranda groans)

144
00:07:02,333 --> 00:07:05,500
...and <i>The Business of Fashion</i>
has already run it.

145
00:07:05,583 --> 00:07:08,208
- (sighs) How bad is it?
- A disaster.

146
00:07:08,291 --> 00:07:10,833
It's gone completely viral.
You want to take a look?

147
00:07:12,041 --> 00:07:13,375
Nigel, can I see that?

148
00:07:13,458 --> 00:07:15,750
- Do I have my glasses on?
- Sorry.

149
00:07:15,833 --> 00:07:18,833
Anyway, you're being blamed
for absolutely everything.

150
00:07:18,916 --> 00:07:21,958
- Oh, God. Irv is gonna flip.
- Yep.

151
00:07:22,041 --> 00:07:23,916
And the timing couldn't be worse.

152
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:25,958
- I know.
- (chuckles)

153
00:07:26,666 --> 00:07:29,250
(Nigel) Chin up. Let's go face the music.

154
00:07:38,791 --> 00:07:40,625
(Miranda) <i>Oh, it's this appalling company</i>

155
00:07:40,708 --> 00:07:42,416
<i>called SpeedFash.</i>

156
00:07:42,500 --> 00:07:44,875
<i>They lied to us about</i>
<i>their working conditions.</i>

157
00:07:44,958 --> 00:07:46,458
<i>They tricked our reporter</i>

158
00:07:46,541 --> 00:07:47,541
and so now,

159
00:07:47,625 --> 00:07:49,458
we are accused of being complicit in

160
00:07:49,541 --> 00:07:52,333
promoting this perfectly horrible company.

161
00:07:52,416 --> 00:07:55,000
The lengths that some people
will go to to turn a profit.

162
00:07:55,083 --> 00:07:57,291
So now we're the villains du jour.

163
00:07:58,791 --> 00:08:01,250
Served up red, piping hot.

164
00:08:02,208 --> 00:08:04,125
Well, good for you, I say.

165
00:08:04,208 --> 00:08:06,333
Villains are always the most interesting.

166
00:08:06,416 --> 00:08:09,166
(phone buzzing)

167
00:08:09,250 --> 00:08:10,250
Oh, God. Irv.

168
00:08:11,750 --> 00:08:14,833
Ah. That is my cue to
take the dog out for a walk.

169
00:08:14,916 --> 00:08:17,791
Hey, Gio! Let's get this done.

170
00:08:17,875 --> 00:08:19,875
- Come on, boy. (whistles)
- (whines, barks)

171
00:08:19,958 --> 00:08:20,791
Hello, Irv.

172
00:08:20,875 --> 00:08:22,500
What the hell, Miranda?

173
00:08:22,583 --> 00:08:24,416
Dad, check this out.

174
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:26,500
We are getting killed online.

175
00:08:26,583 --> 00:08:28,875
I am getting angry emails from ad buyers

176
00:08:28,958 --> 00:08:31,458
- for Tiffany, Fendi, Bvlgari!
- (Miranda) <i>Well, I...</i>

177
00:08:31,541 --> 00:08:33,416
Who's gonna pay for your overpriced book?

178
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:35,458
I've already been on the phone
to advertisers.

179
00:08:35,541 --> 00:08:37,250
I'm meeting with them in the morning

180
00:08:37,333 --> 00:08:39,916
and I'm going to have
a very direct conversation with Ashley.

181
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:41,250
Don't. I'll fix it.

182
00:08:41,833 --> 00:08:43,208
<i>This is abysmal timing.</i>

183
00:08:43,291 --> 00:08:46,625
I'm pondering this huge move
for you. And this happens.

184
00:08:47,875 --> 00:08:49,041
(beeping)

185
00:08:51,583 --> 00:08:53,208
(son) Dad, this is bad.

186
00:08:53,291 --> 00:08:55,375
Even the <i>Journal</i> is thrashing <i>Runway</i>,

187
00:08:55,458 --> 00:08:57,500
and all of Elias-Clarke is getting blamed.

188
00:08:57,583 --> 00:08:58,958
Our monkeys, our circus.

189
00:08:59,041 --> 00:09:00,125
I know.

190
00:09:00,208 --> 00:09:03,083
How are we gonna claw back
any shred of credibility?

191
00:09:04,541 --> 00:09:05,541
Check this out.

192
00:09:07,583 --> 00:09:10,291
<i>Because some things</i>
<i>still matter more than money.</i>

193
00:09:10,375 --> 00:09:12,875
<i>Journalism still fucking matters!</i>

194
00:09:12,958 --> 00:09:14,458
(cheering, whistling)

195
00:09:35,791 --> 00:09:36,625
Whoa.

196
00:09:43,750 --> 00:09:45,708
Yo.

197
00:09:48,583 --> 00:09:50,000
(gulps, gasps)

198
00:09:54,416 --> 00:09:56,416
(host 1) <i>Miranda Priestly?</i>

199
00:09:56,500 --> 00:09:58,166
<i>I thought she was smarter than this.</i>

200
00:09:58,250 --> 00:09:59,791
(host 2) <i>At this point,</i>
<i>it's like you're not relevant.</i>

201
00:09:59,875 --> 00:10:01,166
- (host 1) <i>Oh, my God.</i>
- (host 2) <i>She's a relic.</i>

202
00:10:01,250 --> 00:10:02,583
<i>She's dead. She's a dinosaur.</i>

203
00:10:02,666 --> 00:10:04,166
(host 1) <i>Like, old, tired, washed.</i>

204
00:10:04,250 --> 00:10:05,250
<i>I know it.</i>

205
00:10:05,333 --> 00:10:07,041
<i>She watchin' the season finale</i>
<i>of</i> Yellowstone.

206
00:10:07,125 --> 00:10:09,458
- (host 2) <i>No, fully.</i>
- (hosts laughing)

207
00:10:09,541 --> 00:10:10,541
(phone ringing)

208
00:10:13,750 --> 00:10:14,583
Hello?

209
00:10:14,666 --> 00:10:15,500
(Irv) <i>Andy Sachs?</i>

210
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:16,833
Yes.

211
00:10:16,916 --> 00:10:19,375
<i>Irv Ravitz. Quite a speech you made today.</i>

212
00:10:19,458 --> 00:10:22,125
- Oh. Hi.
- <i>Looks like you need a job.</i>

213
00:10:22,625 --> 00:10:24,916
(♪ Post Animal "Setting Sun" playing)

214
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,041
I can't even believe I'm thinking about

215
00:10:27,125 --> 00:10:28,916
going back to work at that magazine.

216
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:30,833
- How's the salary?
- (inhales deeply)

217
00:10:30,916 --> 00:10:33,750
Twice what I made at the <i>Vanguard</i>

218
00:10:33,833 --> 00:10:35,541
and Irv promised that

219
00:10:35,625 --> 00:10:38,083
I would have a real budget to tell stories

220
00:10:38,166 --> 00:10:40,666
and hire real writers like
you guys, so I don't know.

221
00:10:40,750 --> 00:10:42,833
Hey. No one here is judging you.

222
00:10:42,916 --> 00:10:45,750
I am currently editing a memoir

223
00:10:45,833 --> 00:10:47,875
by one of Paris Hilton's Chihuahuas,

224
00:10:47,958 --> 00:10:50,291
a sassy applehead named Chi-town.

225
00:10:50,375 --> 00:10:52,708
Just to back up, you can hire us.

226
00:10:52,791 --> 00:10:55,625
Your complete abandonment of
your principles means a lot.

227
00:10:55,708 --> 00:10:57,500
(chuckling)

228
00:10:57,583 --> 00:10:59,291
Cheers to that. Pay that rent, man.

229
00:10:59,791 --> 00:11:00,958
(chuckles)

230
00:11:01,041 --> 00:11:02,458
You know what you could do?

231
00:11:02,541 --> 00:11:04,833
If you took the job,
you could write a book.

232
00:11:05,625 --> 00:11:09,583
The definitive Miranda Priestly exposé.

233
00:11:09,666 --> 00:11:10,708
No, I couldn't do that.

234
00:11:10,791 --> 00:11:13,500
An insider's book
about Miranda could be huge.

235
00:11:13,583 --> 00:11:15,041
- I'm gonna text my boss.
- (Andy) No. No, no, no.

236
00:11:15,125 --> 00:11:16,708
- I'm just curious.
- (Andy) Don't you dare.

237
00:11:16,791 --> 00:11:17,916
I bet you could get 50K for it.

238
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:19,958
No, no-- Like, really don't
do that. No, I... No, no, no.

239
00:11:20,041 --> 00:11:22,333
Guys, I would never get hired
again. By anyone.

240
00:11:22,416 --> 00:11:23,541
- She has a point.
- (phone dings)

241
00:11:23,625 --> 00:11:25,166
Some whiny girl
complaining about her boss.

242
00:11:25,250 --> 00:11:27,416
Okay, he said a well-written proposal,

243
00:11:27,500 --> 00:11:28,791
and we all know you do write well,

244
00:11:28,875 --> 00:11:30,166
could get you something like 100K.

245
00:11:30,250 --> 00:11:31,083
No.

246
00:11:31,166 --> 00:11:32,166
(friend 2) Yeah, I'm totally in on this.

247
00:11:32,250 --> 00:11:33,416
No, I'm sorry, I'm just not that person.

248
00:11:33,500 --> 00:11:35,750
I'm not. Maybe I can
make something of this job.

249
00:11:35,833 --> 00:11:39,166
<i>Runway</i> does have a history
of publishing great writing.

250
00:11:39,250 --> 00:11:41,208
No, I'm gonna walk in there tomorrow

251
00:11:41,291 --> 00:11:43,041
with a big smile on my face

252
00:11:43,125 --> 00:11:46,500
and I'm going to make
something of this job. Okay?

253
00:11:57,250 --> 00:11:58,541
What?

254
00:11:58,625 --> 00:12:01,666
"Don't worry. I fixed it.
Be ready at 9:00. Irv."

255
00:12:01,750 --> 00:12:05,041
And you-know-who demanded
we be crosstown at 9:15,

256
00:12:05,125 --> 00:12:06,458
so how do we do both?

257
00:12:06,541 --> 00:12:08,125
We don't have time for this.

258
00:12:08,208 --> 00:12:09,541
What does he mean, "I fixed it"?

259
00:12:09,625 --> 00:12:11,166
(sighs) I have no idea.

260
00:12:11,833 --> 00:12:13,416
- Your 9:00 a.m. is here.
- (Miranda) Hmm.

261
00:12:15,416 --> 00:12:16,416
(gasps)

262
00:12:18,291 --> 00:12:19,541
Hello.

263
00:12:20,291 --> 00:12:21,208
Miranda.

264
00:12:21,291 --> 00:12:23,250
(gasps) Nigel.

265
00:12:23,333 --> 00:12:25,708
Look what TJ Maxx dragged in.

266
00:12:26,291 --> 00:12:28,583
- Hello, Six.
- Hello. (chuckles)

267
00:12:30,375 --> 00:12:33,333
Thank you so much for this opportunity.

268
00:12:33,416 --> 00:12:34,666
I... I've got to admit,

269
00:12:34,750 --> 00:12:36,458
I was really surprised when Irv called.

270
00:12:36,541 --> 00:12:39,000
I mean, a lot of time
has gone by, but I'm just...

271
00:12:40,125 --> 00:12:42,083
I'm so happy for the chance to...

272
00:12:42,166 --> 00:12:43,166
Sorry.

273
00:12:43,250 --> 00:12:45,458
Who is this? Do you know her?
Do I know her?

274
00:12:45,541 --> 00:12:49,333
You might remember Andy.
She was one of the Emilys.

275
00:12:49,416 --> 00:12:50,416
One of the what?

276
00:12:50,500 --> 00:12:52,875
- The Emily from... It's...
- I'm Andy Sachs.

277
00:12:52,958 --> 00:12:54,625
Uh-- Uh, the smart fat girl.

278
00:12:55,666 --> 00:12:57,875
I was one of your assistants eons ago.

279
00:12:57,958 --> 00:12:59,166
Maybe Irv didn't fill you in.

280
00:12:59,250 --> 00:13:01,041
And Irv sent you here to...

281
00:13:01,125 --> 00:13:04,541
To run the Features department.

282
00:13:05,208 --> 00:13:08,333
Be the Features editor.
He hired me last night.

283
00:13:09,041 --> 00:13:10,083
He didn't tell you?

284
00:13:12,625 --> 00:13:13,625
Um...

285
00:13:15,416 --> 00:13:20,000
So he said that, um, we need to, um...

286
00:13:20,083 --> 00:13:23,625
I mean, <i>Runway</i> needs to take control
of the narrative of the SpeedFash story,

287
00:13:23,708 --> 00:13:25,666
and-and-and restore credibility,

288
00:13:25,750 --> 00:13:29,833
and he thought someone with my expertise
would be a good idea,

289
00:13:29,916 --> 00:13:33,958
but I thought that for sure
you had approved and were excited.

290
00:13:34,041 --> 00:13:35,458
And that's why I came in here all like...

291
00:13:35,541 --> 00:13:36,625
(singsongy) ♪ <i>A-oh!</i> ♪

292
00:13:41,208 --> 00:13:42,791
- Amari.
- Yes.

293
00:13:42,875 --> 00:13:44,916
Get Ashley on the phone, please.

294
00:13:46,666 --> 00:13:47,750
(rings, clicks)

295
00:13:47,833 --> 00:13:48,958
(Ashley) <i>Hi. Good morning, Miranda.</i>

296
00:13:49,541 --> 00:13:51,083
Yes, Ashley. Flag on the play.

297
00:13:51,166 --> 00:13:53,916
We don't need you this morning or ever,

298
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:55,625
so pack up your things.

299
00:13:55,708 --> 00:13:58,250
And HR will be in to see you shortly.

300
00:13:58,333 --> 00:13:59,166
Uh...

301
00:13:59,250 --> 00:14:00,250
Happy?

302
00:14:01,333 --> 00:14:04,500
You just cost Cornell
summa cum laude her job.

303
00:14:05,291 --> 00:14:08,208
First in her family to
go to college, I believe.

304
00:14:09,250 --> 00:14:10,666
Anyway, come along.

305
00:14:10,750 --> 00:14:12,250
(Nigel) Come on.

306
00:14:24,541 --> 00:14:25,541
(Andy) Uh...

307
00:14:30,500 --> 00:14:31,500
(grunts)

308
00:14:33,958 --> 00:14:35,791
You should get that looked at.

309
00:14:35,875 --> 00:14:36,750
Hmm?

310
00:14:36,833 --> 00:14:38,916
The injury, or condition, or whatever,

311
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:40,916
that causes you to trudge.

312
00:14:41,625 --> 00:14:42,625
(Miranda sighs)

313
00:14:42,708 --> 00:14:45,250
So, um, I was thinking that...

314
00:14:45,333 --> 00:14:47,625
(clears throat) ...when we
get back to the offices,

315
00:14:47,708 --> 00:14:48,708
we could sit down

316
00:14:48,791 --> 00:14:51,083
and go through some of your priorities.

317
00:14:51,166 --> 00:14:54,333
I could share some of my insights into
the editorial direction of the magazine.

318
00:14:54,416 --> 00:14:59,041
First, though, we need to appease
an important advertiser.

319
00:14:59,125 --> 00:15:00,750
- I-Is that where we're going?
- (Nigel) Yes.

320
00:15:00,833 --> 00:15:02,625
They're furious about SpeedFash.

321
00:15:02,708 --> 00:15:05,833
(sighs) God knows what they're
going to extract from me.

322
00:15:05,916 --> 00:15:08,416
Free ad space, targeted editorial.

323
00:15:08,500 --> 00:15:09,708
A cornea.

324
00:15:10,458 --> 00:15:12,791
Luckily, though, I'm not worried

325
00:15:12,875 --> 00:15:16,583
'cause I have you flown in from on high

326
00:15:16,666 --> 00:15:20,166
to help redirect
this century-old institution

327
00:15:20,250 --> 00:15:23,000
with the benefit of
your infinite wisdom and what?

328
00:15:23,083 --> 00:15:25,208
Oh. Expertise.

329
00:15:25,916 --> 00:15:27,166
Yeah.

330
00:15:28,458 --> 00:15:32,583
Dior constitutes
16% of our designer spend.

331
00:15:32,666 --> 00:15:34,833
And are leading sponsors of
all our special events,

332
00:15:34,916 --> 00:15:35,916
which ain't cheap.

333
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:37,875
Okay, so we fix this, we got this.

334
00:15:37,958 --> 00:15:39,083
Who do we have to talk to?

335
00:15:45,875 --> 00:15:47,541
Am I having a hallucination?

336
00:15:48,166 --> 00:15:49,208
Emily, hi.

337
00:15:50,083 --> 00:15:51,541
Oh, wow.

338
00:15:52,708 --> 00:15:54,625
You also know her?

339
00:15:54,708 --> 00:15:57,375
Well, we were at <i>Runway</i>
at the same time, Miranda.

340
00:15:57,916 --> 00:16:00,041
Really? Where was I?

341
00:16:02,041 --> 00:16:05,291
Right. Um, shall we?

342
00:16:07,833 --> 00:16:09,458
Ms. Charlton, you're glowing.

343
00:16:09,541 --> 00:16:11,291
It seems retail still suits you.

344
00:16:11,375 --> 00:16:14,041
Ah, Nigel, you're hanging in there
by your fingernails.

345
00:16:14,125 --> 00:16:15,916
Remember when magazines were a thing?

346
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:19,125
All right. Come on in, everybody.
Take a seat.

347
00:16:20,208 --> 00:16:22,458
- Lots to discuss.
- (Nigel) Mm-hmm.

348
00:16:23,458 --> 00:16:25,541
Um... Where would you like to start?

349
00:16:26,291 --> 00:16:27,291
(sighs)

350
00:16:27,791 --> 00:16:31,500
Okay. So, um, I'm the new
Features editor at <i>Runway.</i>

351
00:16:31,583 --> 00:16:33,166
No, you're not.

352
00:16:34,791 --> 00:16:36,083
Are you serious?

353
00:16:36,166 --> 00:16:38,750
Wow. Wonders never cease.

354
00:16:38,833 --> 00:16:41,083
No, I'm actually a journalist now.

355
00:16:41,166 --> 00:16:44,666
Um, I've been published in...
It doesn't matter.

356
00:16:44,750 --> 00:16:46,916
Anyway, we are all well aware
that running that story

357
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:48,791
was a mistake and are taking
immediate steps--

358
00:16:48,875 --> 00:16:50,500
I cannot actually get over this.

359
00:16:51,375 --> 00:16:52,916
It's really remarkable.

360
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:56,458
A senior editor at <i>Runway.</i> You.

361
00:16:56,541 --> 00:16:57,708
Yep.

362
00:16:57,791 --> 00:17:00,166
- We're all so thrilled.
- Mm-hmm.

363
00:17:00,250 --> 00:17:03,541
You know what's funny, is you've changed.
You have. You're much more confident.

364
00:17:03,625 --> 00:17:04,458
Oh.

365
00:17:04,541 --> 00:17:06,458
(Emily) Kept those eyebrows
though, didn't you?

366
00:17:06,541 --> 00:17:09,541
Um, right, Miranda. (sighs) How are you?

367
00:17:09,625 --> 00:17:10,833
I mean, what a shambles.

368
00:17:10,916 --> 00:17:13,791
I've had to unruffle so many feathers
because as you know,

369
00:17:13,875 --> 00:17:19,708
our association with <i>Runway</i> and with you
is predicated on your sterling reputation.

370
00:17:19,791 --> 00:17:21,458
(scoffs) Momentary lapse.

371
00:17:21,541 --> 00:17:24,083
And we're doing everything we can
to make it right with you.

372
00:17:24,166 --> 00:17:25,958
Good, 'cause I was
quite shocked reading it.

373
00:17:26,041 --> 00:17:27,666
Though, I'm sure, as you can appreciate,

374
00:17:27,750 --> 00:17:29,708
it's also important that
we have editorial freedom.

375
00:17:29,791 --> 00:17:31,583
We have to maintain
our journalistic integrity.

376
00:17:31,666 --> 00:17:33,625
Ooh. Integrity. I see.

377
00:17:33,708 --> 00:17:36,500
La-di-da, Andy. Very high-minded of you.

378
00:17:36,583 --> 00:17:38,541
Well, please help yourself
to standards galore,

379
00:17:38,625 --> 00:17:41,958
but if there are no advertisers,
there's no <i>Runway.</i>

380
00:17:42,041 --> 00:17:43,291
No us, no you.

381
00:17:43,375 --> 00:17:46,208
- And we understand that completely.
- Oh, good.

382
00:17:46,291 --> 00:17:49,625
I think as a consequence
of your lapse in judgment,

383
00:17:49,708 --> 00:17:52,708
there's just a few things we'd quite like
just to smooth it all over.

384
00:17:52,791 --> 00:17:56,333
We are thinking at least three pages
of advertising credit

385
00:17:56,416 --> 00:17:59,666
and a feature on the opening
of our new flagship.

386
00:18:00,208 --> 00:18:01,416
- Six pages.
- Three.

387
00:18:01,500 --> 00:18:02,500
No. Five.

388
00:18:02,583 --> 00:18:03,458
Four.

389
00:18:03,541 --> 00:18:05,708
I'm sorry. Are we at a fish market, Nigel?

390
00:18:05,791 --> 00:18:08,791
It's five, with brand mentions
in all captions.

391
00:18:10,250 --> 00:18:11,458
Miranda?

392
00:18:11,541 --> 00:18:14,583
Absolutely. We'll get
right on that immediately.

393
00:18:14,666 --> 00:18:15,583
(Emily) Great.

394
00:18:21,791 --> 00:18:24,375
I'm confused. You just
let them tell you what to do?

395
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:26,125
Because if I'm here

396
00:18:26,208 --> 00:18:27,875
to restore your credibility, and I...

397
00:18:27,958 --> 00:18:30,791
Did you not hear her? No them, no us.

398
00:18:30,875 --> 00:18:32,500
We need our advertisers, Andrea.

399
00:18:32,583 --> 00:18:35,416
The September issue is already so thin
you could floss with it.

400
00:18:35,500 --> 00:18:37,208
Yeah, advertisers are important.

401
00:18:37,291 --> 00:18:39,291
I know that. I'm not brand-new, but...

402
00:18:39,375 --> 00:18:40,583
Let's be clear.

403
00:18:41,833 --> 00:18:44,250
You did not earn this job.
I did not hire you.

404
00:18:44,333 --> 00:18:47,708
You are a CEO's latest whim.

405
00:18:47,791 --> 00:18:51,041
And all I need to do is to
bide my time until you fail.

406
00:18:52,750 --> 00:18:54,833
And you will. Fail.

407
00:18:58,333 --> 00:18:59,833
Why don't you take the train, dear?

408
00:19:25,416 --> 00:19:27,291
You got this. You got this.

409
00:19:27,375 --> 00:19:29,041
You... did it.

410
00:19:30,125 --> 00:19:31,125
Okay.

411
00:19:31,208 --> 00:19:32,458
(sighs)

412
00:19:33,708 --> 00:19:34,708
(keys clatter)

413
00:19:37,291 --> 00:19:38,791
They're just eyebrows.

414
00:19:39,791 --> 00:19:41,625
(♪ upbeat music playing)

415
00:19:48,166 --> 00:19:49,416
(elevator bell dings)

416
00:19:49,500 --> 00:19:51,000
(staff chattering)

417
00:20:01,833 --> 00:20:02,875
- Hi!
- Hi.

418
00:20:02,958 --> 00:20:04,416
We weren't properly introduced yesterday.

419
00:20:04,500 --> 00:20:05,500
I'm Andy Sachs.

420
00:20:05,583 --> 00:20:07,041
Charlie. I'm the second assistant.

421
00:20:07,125 --> 00:20:07,958
Hi, Charlie!

422
00:20:08,041 --> 00:20:10,500
Hey. Everybody just calls me
"Charlie the Chair," if you want,

423
00:20:10,583 --> 00:20:12,000
'cause Amari won't let me leave my desk.

424
00:20:12,583 --> 00:20:13,458
Oh, no, it's okay.

425
00:20:13,541 --> 00:20:15,208
(chuckles) A million girls
would kill for this job.

426
00:20:15,291 --> 00:20:17,000
Heard that. (chuckles)

427
00:20:17,083 --> 00:20:18,375
- Is Miranda in?
- There you are.

428
00:20:18,958 --> 00:20:21,375
There you are. I am on time.

429
00:20:21,458 --> 00:20:22,375
So... (scoffs)

430
00:20:22,458 --> 00:20:24,708
...you're the kind of person
who thinks on time is on time.

431
00:20:24,791 --> 00:20:25,625
Okay, got it.

432
00:20:25,708 --> 00:20:27,458
All right, come on.
I'll show you to your office.

433
00:20:27,541 --> 00:20:30,583
Amari, I need to pee.
Please, I had a venti.

434
00:20:30,666 --> 00:20:31,708
Oh.

435
00:20:31,791 --> 00:20:33,208
Was it worth it?

436
00:20:33,291 --> 00:20:34,208
- No.
- No.

437
00:20:34,291 --> 00:20:36,250
Actually, I should probably
talk to Miranda first.

438
00:20:36,333 --> 00:20:37,833
Oh, I'll take you to your office.

439
00:20:38,541 --> 00:20:41,000
- Good luck, Charlie.
- Thanks.

440
00:20:41,541 --> 00:20:43,000
So, I used to have your job.

441
00:20:43,083 --> 00:20:44,916
I heard. Such a remarkable fact.

442
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:48,041
Yeah, back in 2006.

443
00:20:48,125 --> 00:20:49,875
(chuckles) Got to go
to Paris Fashion Week.

444
00:20:49,958 --> 00:20:51,500
Wore a bunch of pieces
from the Chanel collection

445
00:20:51,583 --> 00:20:52,458
that year.

446
00:20:52,541 --> 00:20:54,666
Oh, wait. The one with the pageboy hats?

447
00:20:54,750 --> 00:20:56,708
And the thigh-high boots. Yeah!

448
00:20:56,791 --> 00:20:58,208
Love. Do you still have all of it?

449
00:20:58,291 --> 00:21:00,208
- No, I gave it away.
- What?

450
00:21:00,291 --> 00:21:02,125
Would've been a bit much for a newsroom.

451
00:21:04,416 --> 00:21:05,416
This is you.

452
00:21:05,500 --> 00:21:06,916
Oh. Okay.

453
00:21:13,833 --> 00:21:14,916
And this was Ashley's office?

454
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:17,500
No. Miranda wanted you to have this one,
for some reason.

455
00:21:17,583 --> 00:21:18,750
For some reason. Right.

456
00:21:19,875 --> 00:21:21,375
Who gives away Chanel?

457
00:21:31,791 --> 00:21:33,041
- I stole these for you.
- Hey.

458
00:21:33,791 --> 00:21:35,208
- All from this season.
- (gasps)

459
00:21:35,291 --> 00:21:37,333
But lie about where you got them.

460
00:21:37,833 --> 00:21:40,208
There's more where that came from,
but you can't be greedy.

461
00:21:40,958 --> 00:21:43,291
- Cafeteria?
- Great. I'm all done.

462
00:21:43,375 --> 00:21:44,375
Come on.

463
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:45,833
Hmm.

464
00:21:46,416 --> 00:21:49,458
I don't mind that blazer. Is it...

465
00:21:49,541 --> 00:21:51,166
- Margiela.
- Huh.

466
00:21:51,250 --> 00:21:53,916
Thrifted it in Provo. Eleven bucks.

467
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:55,750
Learned a thing or two the
last time I was here, babe.

468
00:21:55,833 --> 00:21:58,083
Hmm! Not bad, babe.

469
00:21:58,166 --> 00:21:59,708
(Jamiroquai "Diskokid" playing)

470
00:21:59,791 --> 00:22:01,458
Ah, fate.

471
00:22:01,541 --> 00:22:03,875
The winding road
that brings us back to me,

472
00:22:03,958 --> 00:22:06,291
watching you ladle goo into a bowl.

473
00:22:06,375 --> 00:22:07,583
(chuckles)

474
00:22:08,625 --> 00:22:10,041
It's so good to see you, Nigel.

475
00:22:10,125 --> 00:22:11,250
Yeah.

476
00:22:11,333 --> 00:22:13,541
Miranda is very lucky
you're still at the magazine.

477
00:22:14,625 --> 00:22:15,666
What magazine?

478
00:22:15,750 --> 00:22:19,625
You must know that <i>Runway</i>
stopped being a magazine many years ago.

479
00:22:19,708 --> 00:22:23,041
I mean, we still have a book,
but practically nobody buys it.

480
00:22:23,125 --> 00:22:25,875
Nope. We are digital. We are downloadable.

481
00:22:25,958 --> 00:22:28,041
We are streamable. We're in the ether.

482
00:22:29,416 --> 00:22:30,458
And the budgets?

483
00:22:30,541 --> 00:22:33,666
I used to get four weeks
in Africa with Avedon

484
00:22:33,750 --> 00:22:34,958
to do a glossy spread,

485
00:22:35,041 --> 00:22:38,791
and now I'm lucky if I get
two days at Milk Studios

486
00:22:38,875 --> 00:22:43,625
to shoot content that people
scroll past whilst they pee.

487
00:22:46,583 --> 00:22:47,416
(groans)

488
00:22:47,500 --> 00:22:48,916
- So...
- Yeah?

489
00:22:49,833 --> 00:22:54,541
Is it just me, or has Miranda
been extra spicy?

490
00:22:54,625 --> 00:22:56,375
You see her outside of Dior?

491
00:22:56,458 --> 00:22:58,416
I thought her head was going
to spin completely around.

492
00:22:58,500 --> 00:23:01,583
Well, she's on edge
because Irv is about to promote her

493
00:23:01,666 --> 00:23:03,125
to Global Head of Content.

494
00:23:03,208 --> 00:23:04,666
- No way. That's a huge job.
- Yeah.

495
00:23:04,750 --> 00:23:05,625
But the problem is,

496
00:23:05,708 --> 00:23:08,875
the SpeedFash debacle
might derail the whole thing.

497
00:23:08,958 --> 00:23:12,208
What you're saying is, she needs me.

498
00:23:12,291 --> 00:23:13,791
(chuckles)

499
00:23:17,958 --> 00:23:19,875
- Oh, you're serious.
- (chokes)

500
00:23:19,958 --> 00:23:20,791
Sorry.

501
00:23:20,875 --> 00:23:21,708
- Oh, really.
- Yeah.

502
00:23:21,791 --> 00:23:22,791
I'm going up to the art department.

503
00:23:22,875 --> 00:23:24,625
- Oh, you like that.
- (laughing) Yeah, very much.

504
00:23:24,708 --> 00:23:25,791
- Are you Andy?
- Yes.

505
00:23:25,875 --> 00:23:27,583
Hi. I'm Jin Chao. I'm your new assistant.

506
00:23:27,666 --> 00:23:28,666
- Cool! I was wondering...
- Hi.

507
00:23:28,750 --> 00:23:30,166
...about that. Nice to meet you.

508
00:23:30,250 --> 00:23:32,791
I was an intern this morning,
but, uh, when a desk opens up,

509
00:23:32,875 --> 00:23:35,291
the interns get a chance to interview,
and guess what?

510
00:23:35,375 --> 00:23:38,083
Nobody wanted to work in your department
'cause it's not actual fashion,

511
00:23:38,166 --> 00:23:40,208
so I just, like, got it. Isn't that cool?

512
00:23:40,291 --> 00:23:41,125
Very.

513
00:23:41,208 --> 00:23:43,625
- You don't want me.
- (stammers) I didn't say that.

514
00:23:43,708 --> 00:23:45,416
If you don't want me, you can
interview someone else.

515
00:23:45,500 --> 00:23:46,708
- That's totally fine.
- I don't--

516
00:23:46,791 --> 00:23:48,375
I did go to Yale, 3.86 GPA,

517
00:23:48,458 --> 00:23:49,666
lead soprano of the Whiffenpoofs,

518
00:23:49,750 --> 00:23:52,125
and my ACT score was 36
on the very first try, but...

519
00:23:52,208 --> 00:23:53,916
No, you seem great. I'm happy to have you.

520
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:55,333
- Great. Okay. Nice.
- Okay, great. Okay.

521
00:23:55,416 --> 00:23:57,083
Um, so, listen, I'm going
to be working late tonight,

522
00:23:57,166 --> 00:23:59,583
so I'm just going to need
a couple things. First, I j--

523
00:24:00,875 --> 00:24:03,333
Is Miranda hanging up her own coat?

524
00:24:04,375 --> 00:24:06,708
Oh, yeah. I heard there were
some HR complaints.

525
00:24:06,791 --> 00:24:10,083
Apparently, she used to
just throw her coat at people.

526
00:24:10,166 --> 00:24:11,125
Huh.

527
00:24:11,208 --> 00:24:12,208
(closet door slams)

528
00:24:15,875 --> 00:24:17,041
(exhales deeply)

529
00:24:20,416 --> 00:24:21,916
Maybe some things have changed.

530
00:24:22,791 --> 00:24:24,833
Ah. Anyway, yes, working late tonight.

531
00:24:24,916 --> 00:24:26,416
(chattering)

532
00:24:29,083 --> 00:24:31,250
(Andy muttering indistinctly)

533
00:24:41,166 --> 00:24:43,166
You're not still waiting for
the book, are you?

534
00:24:43,250 --> 00:24:45,208
Oh, yeah. She likes hard copies.

535
00:24:45,291 --> 00:24:46,625
(sighs) Still?

536
00:24:46,708 --> 00:24:47,916
(chuckles) Mm-hmm.

537
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:50,125
Um, can I give you something
to bring over to her?

538
00:24:50,208 --> 00:24:51,500
'Course. I'll hoof it over.

539
00:24:51,583 --> 00:24:52,625
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

540
00:24:52,708 --> 00:24:54,375
Oh. When you go to her house,

541
00:24:54,458 --> 00:24:56,125
no matter what anyone tells you,

542
00:24:56,625 --> 00:24:58,583
don't go up the stairs, ever.

543
00:24:58,666 --> 00:24:59,500
(chuckles)

544
00:24:59,583 --> 00:25:00,750
Who'd be stupid enough to do that?

545
00:25:00,833 --> 00:25:01,833
No one!

546
00:25:07,916 --> 00:25:09,125
(phone buzzes)

547
00:25:18,333 --> 00:25:19,333
(chuckles)

548
00:25:26,916 --> 00:25:28,458
Vanessa Friedman in <i>The Times</i>

549
00:25:28,541 --> 00:25:31,833
says that Andy's story
is a "bracing mea culpa."

550
00:25:31,916 --> 00:25:34,833
Yeah, but did anyone
besides culture writers

551
00:25:34,916 --> 00:25:36,500
actually click on the story?

552
00:25:36,583 --> 00:25:40,333
Not really, but optics-wise,
saved our bacon, right?

553
00:25:40,416 --> 00:25:41,916
We'll see. Jury's still out.

554
00:25:44,875 --> 00:25:46,541
(♪ upbeat music playing)

555
00:25:51,958 --> 00:25:53,333
- Good morning.
- Hi.

556
00:25:59,166 --> 00:26:00,208
Nigel in?

557
00:26:00,708 --> 00:26:02,708
No. Nigel's not in.

558
00:26:08,875 --> 00:26:09,875
- I read your piece.
- Hmm?

559
00:26:09,958 --> 00:26:11,250
I read your piece. It was really good.

560
00:26:11,333 --> 00:26:13,000
Oh, thank you. (chuckles)

561
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:16,125
Oh. See, that was a cool profile.

562
00:26:16,208 --> 00:26:18,333
Oh, yeah. The Barnes piece.

563
00:26:18,416 --> 00:26:21,083
Obviously, it was from before their split.

564
00:26:21,166 --> 00:26:22,083
Yeah.

565
00:26:22,166 --> 00:26:23,916
- I love Sasha Barnes.
- I know.

566
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:25,250
(Andy) I've tried to get
an interview with her,

567
00:26:25,333 --> 00:26:27,291
like, a million times
but I've always struck out.

568
00:26:27,375 --> 00:26:29,375
- Oh, you're not the only one.
- Really?

569
00:26:29,458 --> 00:26:30,625
Miranda would kill.

570
00:26:30,708 --> 00:26:33,750
Now that their divorce has made Sasha
one of the richest women in the world.

571
00:26:33,833 --> 00:26:35,333
Interesting.

572
00:26:35,416 --> 00:26:38,083
I feel like I could write a book about
just his before and after.

573
00:26:38,166 --> 00:26:39,166
You know what I mean?

574
00:26:39,250 --> 00:26:40,958
The original Benji Barnes was,
like, that slope-shouldered

575
00:26:41,041 --> 00:26:44,291
nerd who's like, never seen
the inside of a weight room.

576
00:26:44,375 --> 00:26:46,083
Lately... There was a picture
of him the other day.

577
00:26:46,166 --> 00:26:50,541
A few steroids, a smidge
of Sculptra, some Ozempic

578
00:26:50,625 --> 00:26:52,083
- and voilà.
- He's a modern miracle.

579
00:26:52,166 --> 00:26:53,458
It's a modern miracle.

580
00:26:53,541 --> 00:26:54,750
Gotta love a glow up.

581
00:26:54,833 --> 00:26:55,833
It's compelling.

582
00:26:57,000 --> 00:26:59,416
Okay, well-- Ooh. Hi.

583
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:08,750
We took some vintage Muglers
and Westwoods,

584
00:27:08,833 --> 00:27:11,541
and we shot them downtown
in the Washington Mews.

585
00:27:11,625 --> 00:27:12,708
And you were there

586
00:27:13,458 --> 00:27:15,291
when these images were taken?

587
00:27:16,250 --> 00:27:17,458
Uh...

588
00:27:17,541 --> 00:27:19,333
Yes, I-I was.

589
00:27:19,416 --> 00:27:22,125
So the intention was dull and listless.

590
00:27:22,208 --> 00:27:25,125
I wouldn't say that was,
um, the goal. (titters)

591
00:27:25,208 --> 00:27:30,458
And the models were encouraged
to mill around like starving goats

592
00:27:30,541 --> 00:27:34,291
in the parking lot of a methadone clinic
in New Jersey.

593
00:27:34,375 --> 00:27:35,333
(Amari clears throat)

594
00:27:35,416 --> 00:27:36,791
- What?
- Can't say that.

595
00:27:36,875 --> 00:27:38,166
What am I not allowed to say?

596
00:27:38,250 --> 00:27:39,500
- Methadone?
- (Amari) Mmm.

597
00:27:39,583 --> 00:27:41,625
New Jersey? (chuckles)

598
00:27:41,708 --> 00:27:42,541
Anyway...

599
00:27:42,625 --> 00:27:44,750
This was our first time using
this photographer,

600
00:27:44,833 --> 00:27:45,958
so we can do a reshoot.

601
00:27:46,041 --> 00:27:47,708
Just, you know, fix it.

602
00:27:48,708 --> 00:27:53,250
So, who else? Marta?
What do you have cooking?

603
00:27:53,333 --> 00:27:55,708
We're seeing a lot of gorpcore
for this year's resort,

604
00:27:55,791 --> 00:27:59,958
so I was thinking of doing an
interactive piece on the app

605
00:28:00,041 --> 00:28:01,708
where you choose a National Park

606
00:28:01,791 --> 00:28:05,000
and then you choose
a hiking shoe and a bum bag.

607
00:28:05,083 --> 00:28:06,875
A bum bag!

608
00:28:06,958 --> 00:28:09,666
May my suicide be brief and painless.

609
00:28:09,750 --> 00:28:10,625
(Amari clears throat)

610
00:28:10,708 --> 00:28:12,208
- No, no.
- What?

611
00:28:12,291 --> 00:28:13,291
What do you mean, "No, no."

612
00:28:13,375 --> 00:28:17,416
I... I'm not talking about
killing other people. Yet.

613
00:28:19,208 --> 00:28:22,791
Okay. Fine. Uh, who else?

614
00:28:22,875 --> 00:28:23,916
Ilana, what do you have?

615
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:27,791
The re-report of the SpeedFash
story went over well.

616
00:28:27,875 --> 00:28:31,333
Media critics responded to our candor

617
00:28:31,416 --> 00:28:33,625
and to us taking responsibility.

618
00:28:33,708 --> 00:28:37,125
Right. But did anyone read the piece?

619
00:28:37,208 --> 00:28:38,250
I don't know.

620
00:28:38,333 --> 00:28:40,166
Nigel, how are the metrics on that one?

621
00:28:40,708 --> 00:28:42,541
- (Nigel) Mm-mmm.
- Hmm-mmm.

622
00:28:43,166 --> 00:28:48,541
See, you are here to write and edit
features that people read.

623
00:28:48,625 --> 00:28:51,958
And when that happens, yes,
you may interrupt a meeting.

624
00:28:52,708 --> 00:28:55,458
But until then... (winces)

625
00:28:56,458 --> 00:28:57,708
Mm-mmm.

626
00:28:59,083 --> 00:29:03,000
Let's talk about rodeo bow ties.

627
00:29:03,083 --> 00:29:04,041
This one's cute.

628
00:29:05,833 --> 00:29:06,958
That was kinda rough.

629
00:29:07,458 --> 00:29:09,958
I mean, I just steered us
through a crisis.

630
00:29:10,041 --> 00:29:11,666
Is it so hard to acknowledge that?

631
00:29:11,750 --> 00:29:14,666
Oh, yes. The girl who likes validation.

632
00:29:14,750 --> 00:29:15,875
Did your parents hang

633
00:29:15,958 --> 00:29:17,833
all of your finger paintings
up on the fridge?

634
00:29:17,916 --> 00:29:19,083
No. It's not that.

635
00:29:19,166 --> 00:29:20,416
I don't need a pat on the head.

636
00:29:20,500 --> 00:29:22,958
I-I-I need to know what she wants.

637
00:29:23,041 --> 00:29:25,166
All right, I need constructive feedback.

638
00:29:25,250 --> 00:29:26,541
Oh, feedback.

639
00:29:26,625 --> 00:29:29,541
And a lollipop, or... just feedback?

640
00:29:30,958 --> 00:29:32,166
Did you need this job?

641
00:29:33,291 --> 00:29:34,708
Did you take the job?

642
00:29:35,583 --> 00:29:37,583
So figure out a way to do this job.

643
00:29:37,666 --> 00:29:39,125
- Bye.
- Bye.

644
00:29:39,208 --> 00:29:40,875
(Nigel) Bye.

645
00:30:11,791 --> 00:30:13,791
Okay, so I think that if
we're talking about...

646
00:30:13,875 --> 00:30:15,208
Kind of follow that sartorial thing

647
00:30:15,291 --> 00:30:16,500
and how it links up to...

648
00:30:30,375 --> 00:30:31,458
(groans)

649
00:30:41,791 --> 00:30:43,583
What is this?

650
00:30:43,666 --> 00:30:45,041
Oh, that's far too pink, Ken.

651
00:30:45,125 --> 00:30:46,041
We are subtle.

652
00:30:46,125 --> 00:30:47,708
We're not Valentino,
do you know what I mean?

653
00:30:47,791 --> 00:30:50,083
Is this the sample I sent you?
"Tulip whisper."

654
00:30:50,166 --> 00:30:51,166
That's the one.

655
00:30:52,125 --> 00:30:54,458
Now I don't know. I don't know about that.

656
00:30:54,541 --> 00:30:55,791
Wow.

657
00:30:55,875 --> 00:30:57,416
Oh, there she is.

658
00:30:58,166 --> 00:30:59,166
Is this all you?

659
00:30:59,250 --> 00:31:01,375
- It is.
- It's impressive.

660
00:31:01,458 --> 00:31:03,791
You are very busy.
Thank you for your time.

661
00:31:03,875 --> 00:31:07,208
The thinking is that we will
cover the new flagship,

662
00:31:07,291 --> 00:31:08,916
and your role in putting it together.

663
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:10,125
Is that Miranda's idea?

664
00:31:10,208 --> 00:31:11,500
Um, it was mine.

665
00:31:12,291 --> 00:31:14,333
Fine. If that's what you think
is best, then that...

666
00:31:14,416 --> 00:31:15,458
That's fine.

667
00:31:15,541 --> 00:31:16,958
Okay, great. Why don't you,
uh, give me a tour.

668
00:31:17,041 --> 00:31:17,875
Okay. Will do.

669
00:31:17,958 --> 00:31:20,750
Ken, it is not a whisper.
It's a cry for help.

670
00:31:20,833 --> 00:31:23,416
This, of course, is a tribute to
the grand staircase

671
00:31:23,500 --> 00:31:27,208
at the original Dior Atelier
on Avenue Montaigne.

672
00:31:27,291 --> 00:31:29,250
- (Andy) This is incredible.
- I know.

673
00:31:29,333 --> 00:31:30,833
And the cost?

674
00:31:30,916 --> 00:31:32,666
I'm not at liberty to discuss that, Andy,

675
00:31:32,750 --> 00:31:34,791
- but it is whopping.
- (snorts)

676
00:31:34,875 --> 00:31:36,625
What? What is that sickening look?

677
00:31:36,708 --> 00:31:40,166
It's just... It's nice
to see you all grown up.

678
00:31:40,250 --> 00:31:42,166
Ugh. So... So gooey.

679
00:31:42,250 --> 00:31:44,625
Always when you used to make that face...

680
00:31:44,708 --> 00:31:46,166
Because you were always so irritating.

681
00:31:46,250 --> 00:31:48,208
Yeah, you were a barrel of fun.

682
00:31:48,291 --> 00:31:50,333
No, hey, hey, hey. Listen.

683
00:31:50,416 --> 00:31:51,875
I don't know. It's nice to see you again.

684
00:31:51,958 --> 00:31:53,583
- Catch me up. Who are you now?
- No.

685
00:31:53,666 --> 00:31:57,041
Like, not for this, just, human to human.

686
00:31:57,125 --> 00:32:00,833
Fine. I am divorced from
a pathological narcissist. Thank God.

687
00:32:00,916 --> 00:32:02,000
But I've got two beautiful children,

688
00:32:02,083 --> 00:32:02,916
Bronwyn and Roark.

689
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:04,208
One at Collegiate, one at Chapin.

690
00:32:04,750 --> 00:32:06,416
- (Andy) Good for you.
- I know. Gorgeous, right?

691
00:32:06,500 --> 00:32:07,791
- Yeah.
- You?

692
00:32:07,875 --> 00:32:11,041
I... left New York for 15 years.

693
00:32:11,125 --> 00:32:14,166
Just lived everywhere, chasing stories.

694
00:32:14,750 --> 00:32:17,750
And I'm not married.
Never found the right person.

695
00:32:18,250 --> 00:32:21,208
And my kids are
at a doctor's office on 85th.

696
00:32:21,708 --> 00:32:22,833
They're frozen eggs right now,

697
00:32:22,916 --> 00:32:24,458
but I like to think of them
as my little ones.

698
00:32:24,541 --> 00:32:25,750
Siobhan and Esther.

699
00:32:25,833 --> 00:32:26,958
(strained chuckle)

700
00:32:27,041 --> 00:32:28,208
Okay, why did you leave <i>Runway</i>?

701
00:32:28,291 --> 00:32:29,750
I'm sorry, is this an exposé?

702
00:32:29,833 --> 00:32:31,666
- No, it's just a question.
- It's not really relevant.

703
00:32:31,750 --> 00:32:34,541
Well, I mean, you worshipped
that place, and Miranda.

704
00:32:34,625 --> 00:32:36,166
So, why'd you leave?

705
00:32:36,250 --> 00:32:37,833
Why are you even asking me why?

706
00:32:37,916 --> 00:32:39,666
I mean, have a perv around this place.

707
00:32:39,750 --> 00:32:42,875
Luxury retail is the only
sector of the fashion business

708
00:32:42,958 --> 00:32:45,041
that still makes money. That's it. Retail.

709
00:32:45,125 --> 00:32:46,125
Everything else, forget it.

710
00:32:46,208 --> 00:32:48,666
So, yes. Happy to be here, frankly.

711
00:32:48,750 --> 00:32:52,833
Because do you know that 20 years ago,
a $100 handbag was considered a splurge?

712
00:32:52,916 --> 00:32:54,333
Brands like us, we changed all that.

713
00:32:54,916 --> 00:32:58,583
Used logos and branding
because everyone understands,

714
00:32:58,666 --> 00:32:59,916
everyone gets it,

715
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:03,166
that your bag, your scarf,
your perfume, your umbrella...

716
00:33:03,250 --> 00:33:04,083
Write this down.

717
00:33:04,166 --> 00:33:07,083
It tells the world who
you are, what you care about.

718
00:33:07,166 --> 00:33:09,625
And now, there's housewives in Banff

719
00:33:09,708 --> 00:33:12,458
who wouldn't dream of going out
without one of our $3,000 totes.

720
00:33:12,541 --> 00:33:13,500
And that's a good thing?

721
00:33:13,583 --> 00:33:16,208
I don't know. Is it a bad thing
to bring beauty and design to everyone?

722
00:33:16,291 --> 00:33:18,583
Everyone who has $3,000.

723
00:33:18,666 --> 00:33:20,083
Have you heard of Christmas?

724
00:33:20,875 --> 00:33:23,416
Anyway, don't you worry
about me and my career.

725
00:33:23,500 --> 00:33:24,541
Worry about yourself.

726
00:33:25,208 --> 00:33:27,333
I haven't seen any of your
stories get any traction.

727
00:33:27,416 --> 00:33:29,250
Nothing moving the needle there.

728
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:31,416
What does Miranda say about it?

729
00:33:32,416 --> 00:33:33,583
Is she being tough on you?

730
00:33:36,041 --> 00:33:38,083
It's normal Miranda stuff.

731
00:33:38,708 --> 00:33:43,583
Yes, Irv. Yes. I am looking at
the numbers as we speak.

732
00:33:43,666 --> 00:33:44,666
(Irv) <i>They're unacceptable.</i>

733
00:33:44,750 --> 00:33:46,250
- <i>Take care of it!</i>
- Okay, I--

734
00:33:46,333 --> 00:33:47,333
(beeping)

735
00:33:48,666 --> 00:33:49,666
(sighs)

736
00:33:50,291 --> 00:33:52,000
Well, that sounded like a warm bath.

737
00:33:52,083 --> 00:33:55,750
(sighs) It's as if he forgets
he hired her.

738
00:33:56,500 --> 00:33:59,375
His hire, my problem.

739
00:33:59,458 --> 00:34:03,208
Did he say anything at all
about the global editorial job?

740
00:34:03,291 --> 00:34:05,708
No, he's gone mum about all that.

741
00:34:05,791 --> 00:34:08,416
I've spent my career trying to figure out
what people need to know,

742
00:34:08,500 --> 00:34:10,250
now I need to figure out
what people wanna click on.

743
00:34:10,333 --> 00:34:11,333
It's just...

744
00:34:11,416 --> 00:34:14,250
Maybe you just have to figure out
how to do those things at the same time.

745
00:34:14,333 --> 00:34:17,125
You know, like, the smart stuff
and the fun stuff.

746
00:34:17,666 --> 00:34:18,625
Oh, my God.

747
00:34:19,541 --> 00:34:22,708
