You know, I gotta say

1243
00:53:51,666 --> 00:53:54,208
I'm impressed the way you got past
what happened between you and her.

1244
00:53:56,041 --> 00:53:57,875
- What do you mean?
- In Paris.

1245
00:54:00,458 --> 00:54:02,750
When she gave the job
you wanted to Jacqueline.

1246
00:54:02,833 --> 00:54:04,750
(chuckles) Twenty years ago?

1247
00:54:04,833 --> 00:54:07,083
She's done versions of that to me

1248
00:54:07,166 --> 00:54:08,625
a million times since then.

1249
00:54:09,750 --> 00:54:11,291
But here I am.

1250
00:54:12,041 --> 00:54:13,541
By her side.

1251
00:54:13,625 --> 00:54:17,250
Or to the side, you know,
a few steps behind.

1252
00:54:17,333 --> 00:54:19,000
(chuckles)

1253
00:54:19,083 --> 00:54:20,625
And you'd rather be out front?

1254
00:54:21,875 --> 00:54:24,458
Maybe you should tell her what you want.

1255
00:54:25,250 --> 00:54:26,750
What, like you do?

1256
00:54:26,833 --> 00:54:28,500
Like everyone else does?

1257
00:54:28,583 --> 00:54:30,666
Benji, I want you to meet
some of the people

1258
00:54:30,750 --> 00:54:33,000
I worked with at <i>Runway</i>
a gazillion years ago.

1259
00:54:33,083 --> 00:54:34,750
This is, um, Nigel Kipling.

1260
00:54:34,833 --> 00:54:36,583
- Nigel.
- Pleasure.

1261
00:54:36,666 --> 00:54:38,708
And that's Andy...

1262
00:54:38,791 --> 00:54:40,250
- something or other.
- Okay. Andy.

1263
00:54:40,333 --> 00:54:42,583
- Sachs.
- Sorry, can't remember. Sachs.

1264
00:54:42,666 --> 00:54:43,666
- Hi, hi.
- (Benji) Andy. Hi.

1265
00:54:43,750 --> 00:54:47,375
Oh, God. That dress... that is po-pow!

1266
00:54:47,458 --> 00:54:49,166
No, I really hate po-pow. No, no, no.

1267
00:54:49,250 --> 00:54:50,833
Sorry. I'm sorry.

1268
00:54:50,916 --> 00:54:54,166
It's very nice. Not couture,
not custom, but it is nice.

1269
00:54:55,041 --> 00:54:56,083
Say, are you the gal

1270
00:54:56,166 --> 00:54:58,791
who wrote that piece
in <i>Runway </i>about my gal, Emily?

1271
00:54:58,875 --> 00:55:00,500
- Yes. I am.
- Oh, my God.

1272
00:55:00,583 --> 00:55:01,583
I gotta thank you.

1273
00:55:01,666 --> 00:55:06,000
- Really?
- That was so intriguing to me.

1274
00:55:06,083 --> 00:55:07,708
The writing?

1275
00:55:07,791 --> 00:55:08,625
Photos.

1276
00:55:08,708 --> 00:55:10,583
- The photos were so good.
- The subject.

1277
00:55:10,666 --> 00:55:11,916
- Right?
- (glass shatters)

1278
00:55:12,708 --> 00:55:14,791
(♪ dramatic music playing)

1279
00:55:14,875 --> 00:55:15,958
(Miranda screams)

1280
00:55:16,833 --> 00:55:18,458
(guests gasping)

1281
00:55:18,541 --> 00:55:19,958
Oh, my God!

1282
00:55:20,875 --> 00:55:22,541
Is there a doctor?

1283
00:55:22,625 --> 00:55:24,375
Dad? Dad?

1284
00:55:25,541 --> 00:55:27,875
- Oh, my God, Dad.
- Irv.

1285
00:55:27,958 --> 00:55:29,166
Dad?

1286
00:55:32,916 --> 00:55:35,250
(♪ somber music playing)

1287
00:56:00,541 --> 00:56:01,833
Got a lot to think about.

1288
00:56:01,916 --> 00:56:03,958
A day like today really
puts things in perspective

1289
00:56:04,041 --> 00:56:05,791
how fast time moves.

1290
00:56:06,541 --> 00:56:08,833
How we gotta focus on what's important.

1291
00:56:08,916 --> 00:56:10,083
And priorities.

1292
00:56:10,166 --> 00:56:12,291
- (Miranda) Mm-hmm.
- My father loved <i>Runway</i>,

1293
00:56:12,375 --> 00:56:14,708
- you know.
- Yes, he did.

1294
00:56:14,791 --> 00:56:16,166
So did your grandfather.

1295
00:56:16,250 --> 00:56:17,250
Yeah.

1296
00:56:17,333 --> 00:56:18,625
He hired me, you know.

1297
00:56:19,708 --> 00:56:23,208
And when he passed everything
over to Irv... (chuckles)

1298
00:56:23,291 --> 00:56:25,291
- Yeah.
- ...we were the same age.

1299
00:56:25,375 --> 00:56:28,041
We worked so closely.

1300
00:56:28,125 --> 00:56:29,291
Yeah. Right.

1301
00:56:29,375 --> 00:56:30,375
Now it's me and you.

1302
00:56:31,625 --> 00:56:34,250
And I look forward
to carrying that football

1303
00:56:34,750 --> 00:56:36,166
into the end zone together.

1304
00:56:38,250 --> 00:56:39,375
(sighs)

1305
00:56:39,458 --> 00:56:43,458
The end zone. So beautifully put.

1306
00:56:43,541 --> 00:56:45,541
(mourners chattering)

1307
00:56:53,375 --> 00:56:54,541
Isn't this awful?

1308
00:56:56,083 --> 00:56:57,500
I can't believe this is happening.

1309
00:56:57,583 --> 00:56:58,750
It's terribly sad.

1310
00:56:58,833 --> 00:56:59,958
Yes, it is very sad.

1311
00:57:00,041 --> 00:57:02,625
Somehow, Dolce dressed everyone here.

1312
00:57:03,250 --> 00:57:05,916
This entire funeral is their fall '26.

1313
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:07,750
I mean, they must've driven
to everyone's houses

1314
00:57:07,833 --> 00:57:09,083
flinging out freebies, no doubt.

1315
00:57:09,166 --> 00:57:12,250
- Bloody Domenico. So sly.
- (chuckles)

1316
00:57:12,333 --> 00:57:13,708
He'll do anything to get back at me

1317
00:57:13,791 --> 00:57:15,750
since I put Kendall in the finale of '24.

1318
00:57:16,750 --> 00:57:18,166
Isn't she the greatest?

1319
00:57:18,250 --> 00:57:20,666
He's been chomping at the bit
for vengeance.

1320
00:57:20,750 --> 00:57:22,250
- (Benji) Yeah. (chuckles)
- Over Kendall.

1321
00:57:22,333 --> 00:57:24,125
I can't believe there's
someone named Candle.

1322
00:57:28,916 --> 00:57:30,833
What's Jay gonna do? Do you know?

1323
00:57:30,916 --> 00:57:32,875
Do we have any idea what
he's gonna do with <i>Runway</i>?

1324
00:57:32,958 --> 00:57:34,958
No, no. I have no idea,

1325
00:57:35,041 --> 00:57:37,041
but, I mean, you've seen the man.

1326
00:57:37,125 --> 00:57:39,125
He's not exactly a fashion icon.

1327
00:57:39,208 --> 00:57:42,250
He's dressed head to toe
in performance synthetics.

1328
00:57:42,750 --> 00:57:43,666
Throw a match at him

1329
00:57:43,750 --> 00:57:45,666
and he'll go up like
a Christmas tree in March.

1330
00:57:46,583 --> 00:57:48,625
We're gonna be okay, right?

1331
00:57:49,208 --> 00:57:50,791
<i>Runway </i>is still valuable, right?

1332
00:57:50,875 --> 00:57:53,083
I mean, even without Irv.
They know that, right?

1333
00:57:54,041 --> 00:57:56,250
Sorry. So aggressively rhetorical.

1334
00:57:57,208 --> 00:57:58,500
You know, I have no idea.

1335
00:57:58,583 --> 00:58:00,541
We're just going to have to soldier on.

1336
00:58:01,416 --> 00:58:03,000
(horns honking)

1337
00:58:04,208 --> 00:58:06,833
(Nigel)<i> Runway Italy</i>
helped establish Milan

1338
00:58:06,916 --> 00:58:09,041
as one of fashion's most important

1339
00:58:09,125 --> 00:58:10,916
bases of operation,

1340
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:15,000
which is why we can own this

1341
00:58:15,583 --> 00:58:17,000
the Brera Academy.

1342
00:58:17,541 --> 00:58:18,958
We're going to have a custom runway

1343
00:58:19,041 --> 00:58:20,875
that will be for fashion

1344
00:58:20,958 --> 00:58:22,375
as well as musical acts.

1345
00:58:22,458 --> 00:58:23,958
The whole evening is going to kick off

1346
00:58:24,041 --> 00:58:26,791
with one of Miranda's trademark speeches.

1347
00:58:26,875 --> 00:58:28,750
This one will be about the intermingling

1348
00:58:28,833 --> 00:58:31,250
of <i>Runway</i> and Italian couture.

1349
00:58:31,333 --> 00:58:32,958
I'm almost finished
with the speech, by the way.

1350
00:58:33,041 --> 00:58:35,291
It will be in your inbox
by the end of the week.

1351
00:58:35,375 --> 00:58:36,333
Yes, Marta?

1352
00:58:36,416 --> 00:58:38,458
Yeah, this thing
with Irv dying and all that,

1353
00:58:38,541 --> 00:58:40,000
when do we find out if things
are changing around here?

1354
00:58:40,083 --> 00:58:41,541
Yeah, what's Jay's plan for the magazine?

1355
00:58:41,625 --> 00:58:42,583
Is he taking over?

1356
00:58:42,666 --> 00:58:44,208
I mean, does he even like fashion?

1357
00:58:44,291 --> 00:58:45,291
I mean, he wears Drakkar Noir.

1358
00:58:45,375 --> 00:58:46,666
- No, he doesn't.
- Oh, my God.

1359
00:58:46,750 --> 00:58:49,041
I'd like to talk about the looks

1360
00:58:49,125 --> 00:58:53,375
that we're going to feature
in the Brera Academy show.

1361
00:58:53,458 --> 00:58:56,333
Some of the bodies
are very interesting, very...

1362
00:58:57,916 --> 00:58:59,791
body... negative.

1363
00:58:59,875 --> 00:59:01,000
(clears throat)

1364
00:59:01,083 --> 00:59:06,166
No, don't tell me.
I know this. Body positive.

1365
00:59:08,166 --> 00:59:11,208
(sighs) But why, really?
When you think a--

1366
00:59:11,291 --> 00:59:12,625
(Dirk) Oh, my God. He's here.

1367
00:59:12,708 --> 00:59:13,833
(Amari gasps)

1368
00:59:13,916 --> 00:59:16,208
(staff member 1) Yeah,
that's, like, our new owner.

1369
00:59:26,708 --> 00:59:28,291
(♪ tense music playing)

1370
00:59:30,250 --> 00:59:32,125
Always loved your office.

1371
00:59:32,208 --> 00:59:33,958
Can't get views like this anymore.

1372
00:59:34,041 --> 00:59:34,875
(Miranda) Mmm.

1373
00:59:34,958 --> 00:59:38,333
And the size. I mean, wow.

1374
00:59:38,416 --> 00:59:40,666
(Miranda) I remember
you coming to the offices

1375
00:59:40,750 --> 00:59:42,541
as a kid with your father

1376
00:59:43,708 --> 00:59:45,625
and your little lacrosse stick,

1377
00:59:45,708 --> 00:59:48,208
tossing that ball up all around.

1378
00:59:48,291 --> 00:59:49,750
I broke a vase.

1379
00:59:49,833 --> 00:59:52,041
Did you? I don't remember.

1380
00:59:52,125 --> 00:59:54,083
Anyway, sorry it took me a while

1381
00:59:54,166 --> 00:59:57,166
to stop by or call you back.

1382
00:59:57,250 --> 00:59:58,625
We barely noticed.

1383
00:59:58,708 --> 01:00:01,500
But now I'm ready to get ducks in rows,

1384
01:00:01,583 --> 01:00:05,375
kick some concepts around
with you, check boxes. Lunch?

1385
01:00:06,083 --> 01:00:08,875
- Now?
- Bad time? You slammed?

1386
01:00:08,958 --> 01:00:10,166
No, not at all.

1387
01:00:10,250 --> 01:00:12,750
I'll just get someone
to make a reservation at--

1388
01:00:12,833 --> 01:00:13,958
Oh, cafeteria's fine.

1389
01:00:14,041 --> 01:00:16,916
I have a couple calls
that I should return anyway.

1390
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:19,875
Um, I will see you there in ten.

1391
01:00:25,208 --> 01:00:26,541
Amari?

1392
01:00:28,208 --> 01:00:29,041
Yes?

1393
01:00:29,125 --> 01:00:31,041
We have a cafeteria?

1394
01:00:31,583 --> 01:00:33,000
- Oh, yes.
- Really?

1395
01:00:35,875 --> 01:00:36,875
(phone chimes)

1396
01:00:39,291 --> 01:00:40,500
Cafeteria?

1397
01:00:41,958 --> 01:00:44,458
She's never even been to that floor.

1398
01:00:44,541 --> 01:00:45,833
(elevator bell dings)

1399
01:00:48,791 --> 01:00:49,791
It's frozen again.

1400
01:00:49,875 --> 01:00:51,208
(staff chattering)

1401
01:00:51,291 --> 01:00:52,833
Be back in 20 minutes.

1402
01:00:52,916 --> 01:00:54,416
(chattering stops)

1403
01:00:56,791 --> 01:00:59,041
Hey. What's good here?

1404
01:00:59,541 --> 01:01:00,458
Um...

1405
01:01:00,541 --> 01:01:01,375
All the...

1406
01:01:03,958 --> 01:01:04,791
things.

1407
01:01:04,875 --> 01:01:05,875
You know what?

1408
01:01:05,958 --> 01:01:07,208
Before we eat,

1409
01:01:07,291 --> 01:01:09,250
why don't I introduce you
to some of the guys.

1410
01:01:09,333 --> 01:01:11,666
People. Some of the people.

1411
01:01:11,750 --> 01:01:14,916
Didn't mean to, uh, spring all
these folks on you at once.

1412
01:01:15,000 --> 01:01:16,000
And yet...

1413
01:01:16,083 --> 01:01:18,875
These are just some
consultants that I brought in

1414
01:01:18,958 --> 01:01:20,250
for the restructure.

1415
01:01:20,333 --> 01:01:24,375
The best guys. People, the best people.

1416
01:01:24,458 --> 01:01:26,791
They'll be weighing in on
our organizational alignment,

1417
01:01:26,875 --> 01:01:29,916
operational strategy,
financial architecture,

1418
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:34,458
digital transformation,
user experience, everything.

1419
01:01:35,083 --> 01:01:36,083
Everything.

1420
01:01:36,166 --> 01:01:38,000
Sandeep, you wanna fill Ms. Priestly in

1421
01:01:38,083 --> 01:01:39,250
on our concepts?

1422
01:01:39,333 --> 01:01:42,625
Absolutely. Sandeep Kapoor,
Harvard MBA. Not important.

1423
01:01:43,166 --> 01:01:45,958
You know, at our offices,
we call you "Miranda Beastly"

1424
01:01:46,041 --> 01:01:47,333
'cause you're a beast in the game.

1425
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:49,833
And unfortunately, right now
what's happening is

1426
01:01:49,916 --> 01:01:51,250
that beast is leashed.

1427
01:01:51,333 --> 01:01:54,625
And we need to let that
beast free. Let it roam.

1428
01:01:55,291 --> 01:01:57,250
Ugh. Undertakers.

1429
01:01:58,166 --> 01:02:00,708
No, what? Management consultants.

1430
01:02:00,791 --> 01:02:01,875
Like I said.

1431
01:02:01,958 --> 01:02:03,291
(Nigel) McKinsey to my eye.

1432
01:02:03,375 --> 01:02:04,916
(Andy) Pfft. Cute.

1433
01:02:05,916 --> 01:02:07,500
(whispers) Wish I could hear
what they were saying.

1434
01:02:07,583 --> 01:02:08,791
- I know.
- (Andy sighs)

1435
01:02:08,875 --> 01:02:10,125
Anyone want Froyo?

1436
01:02:11,166 --> 01:02:13,500
- What?
- What? Best thing here.

1437
01:02:14,291 --> 01:02:15,791
(♪ suspenseful music playing)

1438
01:02:18,166 --> 01:02:20,333
I worry about this generation of kids.

1439
01:02:20,416 --> 01:02:22,250
It's a national emergency.

1440
01:02:27,500 --> 01:02:29,500
It went on for an hour.

1441
01:02:29,583 --> 01:02:32,666
Miranda in the middle
of that circle of suits.

1442
01:02:32,750 --> 01:02:34,333
I have no idea what was agreed to.

1443
01:02:34,416 --> 01:02:35,458
They're gonna cut Features first.

1444
01:02:35,541 --> 01:02:36,666
They always cut the writing first.

1445
01:02:36,750 --> 01:02:38,666
Look, look... (sighs)

1446
01:02:38,750 --> 01:02:41,000
...Miranda is resourceful, all right?

1447
01:02:41,083 --> 01:02:42,958
Whatever this new situation
is, she'll find a way.

1448
01:02:43,041 --> 01:02:44,833
Trust me. (scoffing)
She is always ten steps ahead.

1449
01:02:44,916 --> 01:02:46,208
Well, it's just, you know,
this whole thing

1450
01:02:46,291 --> 01:02:47,458
of having an actual job,

1451
01:02:47,541 --> 01:02:50,583
it's been, like, great, you know?

1452
01:02:50,666 --> 01:02:52,083
Yeah, I know.

1453
01:02:52,166 --> 01:02:53,083
- Hi, hi.
- (coworker) Oh, boy.

1454
01:02:53,166 --> 01:02:54,250
I need to talk to you right now.

1455
01:02:54,333 --> 01:02:56,458
Okay. Okay. Excuse me, please. What?

1456
01:02:56,541 --> 01:02:57,583
Okay.

1457
01:02:57,666 --> 01:02:59,375
You know you said
that you wanted to know about

1458
01:02:59,458 --> 01:03:00,666
what Miranda and Jay were talking about

1459
01:03:00,750 --> 01:03:01,625
in the cafeteria.

1460
01:03:01,708 --> 01:03:02,708
Yeah.

1461
01:03:02,791 --> 01:03:03,875
So...

1462
01:03:04,416 --> 01:03:05,250
What is that?

1463
01:03:05,333 --> 01:03:06,458
When I was getting Froyo,

1464
01:03:06,541 --> 01:03:07,833
I dropped my spoon on the floor,

1465
01:03:07,916 --> 01:03:09,125
and I put my phone under her chair,

1466
01:03:09,208 --> 01:03:12,500
and it was recording the whole time.

1467
01:03:12,583 --> 01:03:13,833
(♪ mischievous music playing)

1468
01:03:14,375 --> 01:03:15,416
Jin!

1469
01:03:15,500 --> 01:03:19,250
- Yeah. Yup, yup, yup, yup.
- What? You are such a badass!

1470
01:03:19,333 --> 01:03:20,416
Yeah, I know.

1471
01:03:21,583 --> 01:03:22,750
(Jay)<i> We took a look at your budget</i>

1472
01:03:22,833 --> 01:03:26,041
<i>and have some immediate</i>
<i>ideas for scale-downs.</i>

1473
01:03:26,125 --> 01:03:29,125
<i>Show the markets that we are</i>
<i>ready to crank that EBITDA.</i>

1474
01:03:29,208 --> 01:03:30,583
I'm just gonna...

1475
01:03:32,625 --> 01:03:34,208
(exhales deeply)

1476
01:03:34,291 --> 01:03:35,666
You don't wanna know.

1477
01:03:35,750 --> 01:03:37,541
Then don't tell me.

1478
01:03:37,625 --> 01:03:39,416
Oh... Oh.

1479
01:03:40,833 --> 01:03:44,541
I was kidding. What is it? Spill it.

1480
01:03:44,625 --> 01:03:48,250
(whispering) Nigel,
they're cutting everything.

1481
01:03:49,250 --> 01:03:51,875
Features? Reduced to nothing.

1482
01:03:51,958 --> 01:03:53,458
Fashion and Beauty? Decimated.

1483
01:03:53,541 --> 01:03:55,083
Cuts across all departments,

1484
01:03:55,166 --> 01:03:57,166
and anyone who's been here
for longer than five years

1485
01:03:57,250 --> 01:03:58,833
is too expensive and has to go.

1486
01:03:58,916 --> 01:03:59,916
I'm sorry.

1487
01:04:01,333 --> 01:04:02,541
That makes sense.

1488
01:04:02,625 --> 01:04:04,458
- And you know what she said?
- (Nigel) Nope.

1489
01:04:04,541 --> 01:04:06,333
Not a single thing.

1490
01:04:08,500 --> 01:04:09,500
Nigel.

1491
01:04:13,875 --> 01:04:15,083
You know what I think?

1492
01:04:16,166 --> 01:04:21,291
I think I like the bag cross-body.

1493
01:04:24,791 --> 01:04:26,083
That's what I think.

1494
01:04:28,625 --> 01:04:29,625
All right.

1495
01:04:30,291 --> 01:04:31,500
I'll leave you to it.

1496
01:04:40,791 --> 01:04:43,083
(The Marias “No One Noticed” playing)

1497
01:04:43,166 --> 01:04:45,375
I just can't believe
this is happening again.

1498
01:04:45,458 --> 01:04:47,458
Another publication, deleted.

1499
01:04:49,375 --> 01:04:52,333
- I'm sorry, Andy. It sucks.
- Sucks.

1500
01:04:56,541 --> 01:04:58,541
This is where it's all going,
you know? It's...

1501
01:04:59,041 --> 01:04:59,916
It's happening all over.

1502
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:01,333
It's pharmacies, it's bookstores.

1503
01:05:01,416 --> 01:05:02,250
It's... You name it.

1504
01:05:02,333 --> 01:05:04,833
It's all being downsized.
It's all consolidating.

1505
01:05:04,916 --> 01:05:06,750
No, I just can't accept that. I--

1506
01:05:06,833 --> 01:05:09,541
We... We can't just keep

1507
01:05:09,625 --> 01:05:11,750
sucking the soul out of everything.

1508
01:05:11,833 --> 01:05:14,625
And-and gutting it
and then repackaging it.

1509
01:05:14,708 --> 01:05:16,208
To what end?

1510
01:05:16,750 --> 01:05:19,583
But it's... it's...
We're replacing it, you know?

1511
01:05:19,666 --> 01:05:21,083
I mean, you've basically just described

1512
01:05:21,166 --> 01:05:22,458
what I've done with this building.

1513
01:05:23,166 --> 01:05:25,875
Peter, we're not talking about
you right now. We're talk--

1514
01:05:25,958 --> 01:05:27,083
And also, like,

1515
01:05:27,166 --> 01:05:31,250
journalism matters
more than luxury apartments.

1516
01:05:33,333 --> 01:05:34,416
That's true.

1517
01:05:36,458 --> 01:05:38,125
I'm sorry. I'm just...

1518
01:05:38,750 --> 01:05:41,041
This is such a spectacularly
helpful conversation.

1519
01:05:41,125 --> 01:05:41,958
Thank you.

1520
01:05:42,041 --> 01:05:43,583
- Is it not?
- No.

1521
01:05:49,750 --> 01:05:51,583
I might give you a minute.

1522
01:05:51,666 --> 01:05:52,791
Thanks.

1523
01:05:58,791 --> 01:06:01,041
Hey, I, uh...
I know you gotta go to Italy,

1524
01:06:01,125 --> 01:06:02,750
but if you wanna... (sighs)

1525
01:06:03,708 --> 01:06:05,625
...if you wanna catch up
when you're back, I'd like it.

1526
01:06:06,791 --> 01:06:08,083
But it's up to you.

1527
01:06:12,291 --> 01:06:13,291
(door closes)

1528
01:06:13,958 --> 01:06:16,458
- (horns honking)
- (dogs barking in distance)

1529
01:06:32,416 --> 01:06:33,416
(doorbell chimes)

1530
01:06:34,750 --> 01:06:35,833
Hmm, no.

1531
01:06:37,166 --> 01:06:39,083
- Oh, hi, Stuart.
- Andy.

1532
01:06:39,166 --> 01:06:40,458
- Yes.
- You all right?

1533
01:06:40,541 --> 01:06:42,916
- (stammers) Could I come in?
- Sure, absolutely.

1534
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:44,958
Um, wasn't expecting you, I suppose.

1535
01:06:45,041 --> 01:06:49,708
Sorry to bother you.
I just, um, need, uh...

1536
01:06:49,791 --> 01:06:51,541
- I think... (inhales deeply)
- Catch your breath maybe.

1537
01:06:51,625 --> 01:06:54,291
Okay. Can't. Um, is she here?

1538
01:06:54,791 --> 01:06:56,666
Yeah, she's, um...

1539
01:07:03,750 --> 01:07:04,916
Brave.

1540
01:07:07,583 --> 01:07:08,583
Ah.

1541
01:07:09,416 --> 01:07:11,541
I don't mean to bother you.
I just need to talk.

1542
01:07:12,666 --> 01:07:14,583
- Talk.
- So, uh, I just need to...

1543
01:07:14,666 --> 01:07:16,833
I just need to... You have a plan, right?

1544
01:07:16,916 --> 01:07:18,458
A secret plan like...

1545
01:07:18,541 --> 01:07:19,958
- like you did--
- I can't hear you.

1546
01:07:20,041 --> 01:07:21,875
Don't you have people you can call?

1547
01:07:21,958 --> 01:07:24,375
I just don't want everyone
to lose their jobs.

1548
01:07:24,458 --> 01:07:25,291
Please, Miranda,

1549
01:07:25,375 --> 01:07:27,208
we have been doing such great work lately.

1550
01:07:27,291 --> 01:07:28,916
We're attracting great writers,

1551
01:07:29,000 --> 01:07:31,458
and people care about the magazine again.

1552
01:07:31,541 --> 01:07:33,875
This job has let me hope again

1553
01:07:33,958 --> 01:07:35,625
for the future, for our future, my future.

1554
01:07:35,708 --> 01:07:37,541
I... I might be able to unfreeze an egg.

1555
01:07:37,625 --> 01:07:38,750
Go home.

1556
01:07:38,833 --> 01:07:40,666
- But I...
- It's late.

1557
01:07:40,750 --> 01:07:43,750
Do not concern yourself with this.

1558
01:07:46,083 --> 01:07:48,625
(quietly) It does not concern you.

1559
01:07:54,583 --> 01:07:56,583
(♪ somber music playing)

1560
01:08:01,541 --> 01:08:03,208
(sighs)

1561
01:08:12,416 --> 01:08:14,875
Hmm. Huh.

1562
01:08:19,958 --> 01:08:20,958
(sighs)

1563
01:08:26,083 --> 01:08:28,083
(keyboard clicking)

1564
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:34,791
<i>Allora, Milano...</i>

1565
01:08:34,875 --> 01:08:37,166
Nigel, you were saying
that some new directives

1566
01:08:37,250 --> 01:08:39,333
have come in from on high.

1567
01:08:40,375 --> 01:08:41,666
Budget cuts?

1568
01:08:41,750 --> 01:08:44,625
Yes, so, regarding Milan,

1569
01:08:44,708 --> 01:08:47,000
we're cutting John Legend

1570
01:08:47,083 --> 01:08:49,083
because he wants us to ship
his piano there,

1571
01:08:49,166 --> 01:08:50,333
and that's too pricey.

1572
01:08:50,416 --> 01:08:52,041
So, no music.

1573
01:08:53,041 --> 01:08:54,375
Unless we call in a favor.

1574
01:08:54,458 --> 01:08:55,291
(pen clicks)

1575
01:08:57,125 --> 01:08:58,166
No.

1576
01:09:02,416 --> 01:09:04,500
No. She's impossible.

1577
01:09:04,583 --> 01:09:06,083
That cover almost...

1578
01:09:07,541 --> 01:09:08,375
killed me.

1579
01:09:08,458 --> 01:09:13,583
Fine. No music. None at all. No music.

1580
01:09:13,666 --> 01:09:15,583
- Okay, fine. I'll call her.
- Thank you.

1581
01:09:15,666 --> 01:09:19,500
Now, there are a few new
policies across the board.

1582
01:09:19,583 --> 01:09:23,916
The first one is no more
private cars. Uber only.

1583
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:24,833
(gasps)

1584
01:09:24,916 --> 01:09:27,916
And as for the flights...

1585
01:09:30,791 --> 01:09:32,250
<i>Good afternoon, ladies and gentlemen,</i>

1586
01:09:32,333 --> 01:09:35,000
<i>and welcome aboard</i>
<i>United Airlines Flight 19</i>

1587
01:09:35,083 --> 01:09:37,000
<i>with service to Milan, Italy.</i>

1588
01:09:37,083 --> 01:09:38,666
<i>We'll be coming by with champagne</i>

1589
01:09:38,750 --> 01:09:41,375
<i>for our Polaris business</i>
<i>class passengers shortly.</i>

1590
01:09:41,458 --> 01:09:44,416
<i>If you're seated in economy,</i>
<i>we do have a full flight today</i>

1591
01:09:44,500 --> 01:09:47,041
<i>so please stow your carry-ons</i>
<i>in the overhead compartments</i>

1592
01:09:47,125 --> 01:09:49,875
<i>above you and secure any</i>
<i>personal bags or belongings</i>

1593
01:09:49,958 --> 01:09:51,541
<i>under the seat in front of you.</i>

1594
01:09:52,041 --> 01:09:54,541
I need some... Get me something to drink.

1595
01:10:01,625 --> 01:10:03,166
What is wrong with Miranda?

1596
01:10:03,250 --> 01:10:04,791
Why is she putting up with this?

1597
01:10:05,416 --> 01:10:07,250
Excuse me. Excuse me.

1598
01:10:07,333 --> 01:10:08,875
Uh, Ms. Priestly would like a glass

1599
01:10:08,958 --> 01:10:10,125
of your finest champagne.

1600
01:10:10,208 --> 01:10:12,500
I'm sorry. That's not served
in this cabin.

1601
01:10:13,083 --> 01:10:14,625
They have snack boxes.

1602
01:10:15,375 --> 01:10:16,916
Mmm. Um... (clears throat)

1603
01:10:17,000 --> 01:10:18,500
A snack box perhaps?

1604
01:10:20,583 --> 01:10:22,583
(♪ Madonna "Vogue" playing)

1605
01:10:24,666 --> 01:10:25,666
♪ <i>Vogue</i> ♪

1606
01:10:27,166 --> 01:10:29,166
- (people chattering)
- (photographers clamoring)

1607
01:10:29,250 --> 01:10:30,750
♪ <i>Look around</i> ♪

1608
01:10:30,833 --> 01:10:33,125
♪ <i>Everywhere you turn Is heartache </i>♪

1609
01:10:33,208 --> 01:10:37,541
♪ <i>It's everywhere that you go</i>
<i>Look around </i>♪

1610
01:10:37,625 --> 01:10:41,333
♪ <i>You try everything you can To escape</i> ♪

1611
01:10:41,416 --> 01:10:43,708
♪ <i>The pain of life That you know</i> ♪

1612
01:10:43,791 --> 01:10:45,041
♪ <i>Life that you know </i>♪

1613
01:10:45,125 --> 01:10:48,791
♪ <i>When all else fails And you long to be</i> ♪

1614
01:10:48,875 --> 01:10:52,125
♪ <i>Something better Than you are today</i> ♪

1615
01:10:53,750 --> 01:10:56,791
♪ <i>I know a place Where you can get away</i> ♪

1616
01:10:56,875 --> 01:10:58,916
♪ <i>It's called a dance floor</i> ♪

1617
01:10:59,000 --> 01:11:00,958
♪ <i>And here's what it's for</i> ♪

1618
01:11:01,041 --> 01:11:03,416
♪ <i>So come on, vogue</i> ♪

1619
01:11:03,500 --> 01:11:04,750
♪ <i>Vogue</i> ♪

1620
01:11:04,833 --> 01:11:08,208
♪ <i>Let your body Move to the music</i> ♪

1621
01:11:08,291 --> 01:11:09,958
♪ <i>Hey, hey, hey</i> ♪

1622
01:11:10,041 --> 01:11:11,791
♪ <i>Come on, vogue</i> ♪

1623
01:11:11,875 --> 01:11:13,000
♪ <i>Vogue</i> ♪

1624
01:11:13,083 --> 01:11:15,875
♪ <i>Let your body Go with the flow</i> ♪

1625
01:11:15,958 --> 01:11:18,416
♪ <i>You know you can do it</i> ♪

1626
01:11:30,666 --> 01:11:32,333
Oh, it's so beautiful!

1627
01:11:33,708 --> 01:11:34,833
Just click it.

1628
01:11:36,458 --> 01:11:38,708
- (Benji) Look at that.
- (Emily) What do you think?

1629
01:11:38,791 --> 01:11:42,875
- Oh, yeah. Uh-huh.
- What do you think, Benji?

1630
01:11:42,958 --> 01:11:44,125
(sighs)

1631
01:11:44,208 --> 01:11:45,500
What are you doing?

1632
01:11:45,583 --> 01:11:47,916
Uh... (chuckles) Got hypnotized.

1633
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:49,833
Benji's buying Emily a very nice necklace.

1634
01:11:49,916 --> 01:11:52,083
Yes, I'm not surprised.

1635
01:11:52,166 --> 01:11:54,083
Last week, he bought her a Monet.

1636
01:11:55,291 --> 01:11:56,208
And a Klimt.

1637
01:11:56,291 --> 01:11:58,166
- Really?
- Oh, yes.

1638
01:11:59,625 --> 01:12:00,458
Come on.

1639
01:12:00,541 --> 01:12:02,125
- What?
- No, I mean, we're gonna--

1640
01:12:02,208 --> 01:12:04,416
Hey, just put it on my tab
here. Just put it on my tab.

1641
01:12:04,500 --> 01:12:06,083
Ah. <i>Pronto</i>?

1642
01:12:06,166 --> 01:12:09,083
<i>Pronto, sì, pronto. </i>Um...

1643
01:12:09,166 --> 01:12:12,708
<i>Posso avere il numero di camera...</i>

1644
01:12:13,958 --> 01:12:15,583
Yes, I need a room number.

1645
01:12:15,666 --> 01:12:17,833
<i>Mommy, Roark said he wants</i>

1646
01:12:17,916 --> 01:12:19,458
<i>the éclair from Miss Madeleine,</i>

1647
01:12:19,541 --> 01:12:21,458
<i>but it was my idea to go there.</i>

1648
01:12:21,541 --> 01:12:23,833
Oh, bunny, what do we do
when we get a bit wobbly?

1649
01:12:23,916 --> 01:12:24,875
We... That's right.

1650
01:12:24,958 --> 01:12:27,250
- Breathe in, hold...
<i>- </i>(Bronwyn) <i>Breathe in, hold.</i>

1651
01:12:27,333 --> 01:12:28,166
(inhales deeply)

1652
01:12:28,250 --> 01:12:29,250
...and breathe out.

1653
01:12:29,333 --> 01:12:30,416
And don't forget to do the tappy-tap,

1654
01:12:30,500 --> 01:12:32,125
tappy-tap it all away.

1655
01:12:32,208 --> 01:12:34,208
- There we are. Is that better?
<i>- </i>(Bronwyn) <i>Uh-huh.</i>

1656
01:12:34,291 --> 01:12:36,375
Okay, my love. Now, listen,
can you go get Daddy?

1657
01:12:36,458 --> 01:12:38,208
All right. Love ya.

1658
01:12:38,291 --> 01:12:39,875
<i>- What's up?</i>
- Frank.

1659
01:12:39,958 --> 01:12:41,875
I am in Milan, and as you can see,

1660
01:12:41,958 --> 01:12:43,875
I am stretched thinner
than a pair of Spanx,

1661
01:12:43,958 --> 01:12:46,083
so can you just try parenting?

1662
01:12:46,166 --> 01:12:47,125
Go to Miss Madeleine

1663
01:12:47,208 --> 01:12:48,208
and get them the bloody éclair.

1664
01:12:48,291 --> 01:12:49,625
- I can't do everything.
<i>- You went to Italy.</i>

1665
01:12:49,708 --> 01:12:51,000
<i>I'm here. So...</i>

1666
01:12:59,916 --> 01:13:02,666
(exhales)

1667
01:13:02,750 --> 01:13:06,500
May the bridges I burn light my way.

1668
01:13:07,125 --> 01:13:08,916
- (knocking on door)
- God.

1669
01:13:16,333 --> 01:13:17,416
Hi.

1670
01:13:17,500 --> 01:13:18,875
- (Emily) Andy.
- Do you have a sec?

1671
01:13:18,958 --> 01:13:20,708
- Yes.
- Okay.

1672
01:13:22,750 --> 01:13:23,750
(elevator bell dings)

1673
01:13:25,583 --> 01:13:27,583
(♪ adventurous music playing)

1674
01:13:28,708 --> 01:13:29,791
Okay.

1675
01:13:29,875 --> 01:13:31,291
Well, hello.

1676
01:13:31,375 --> 01:13:33,958
- Hi. (chuckles)
- Look at us, up before dawn.

1677
01:13:34,041 --> 01:13:35,541
I just went for a stroll.
What are you doing?

1678
01:13:35,625 --> 01:13:37,541
- Me? Um...
- Yeah. Where are you going?

1679
01:13:37,625 --> 01:13:38,958
- Como.
- Ah.

1680
01:13:39,041 --> 01:13:40,583
Yeah, I'm doing that story on the winery.

1681
01:13:40,666 --> 01:13:42,166
Oh. Right, right.

1682
01:13:42,250 --> 01:13:43,166
That's cute.

1683
01:13:43,250 --> 01:13:44,250
Dinner tonight?

1684
01:13:44,333 --> 01:13:46,208
I always eat with Tom Ford at Da Giacomo.

1685
01:13:46,291 --> 01:13:47,875
- Little gossip sesh? Hmm?
- Uh-huh. Um.

1686
01:13:47,958 --> 01:13:49,166
Okay, great. I'll text you.

1687
01:13:49,250 --> 01:13:50,250
- Okay.
- Okay.

1688
01:13:53,666 --> 01:13:54,500
Hmm.

1689
01:13:56,166 --> 01:13:57,000
(Emily) Come on.

1690
01:13:57,083 --> 01:13:58,750
Window up. Window up.
Nigel's watching. Nigel.

1691
01:13:58,833 --> 01:14:00,666
What? Bloody hell.

1692
01:14:35,708 --> 01:14:37,541
(laughs)

1693
01:14:38,208 --> 01:14:39,375
There she is.

1694
01:14:39,458 --> 01:14:42,333
Oh, hi, honey. Hi. Don't.

1695
01:14:42,416 --> 01:14:44,208
I'm sorry. I'm just saying, "hello."

1696
01:14:48,375 --> 01:14:49,916
So how long have you had a place here?

1697
01:14:51,250 --> 01:14:52,375
- Me?
- Mm-hmm.

1698
01:14:52,458 --> 01:14:54,125
- Oh, God. Um...
- (in Italian) <i>Grazie.</i>

1699
01:14:54,208 --> 01:14:55,291
(laughs)

1700
01:14:55,375 --> 01:14:56,500
(in English) I don't know. I don't know.

1701
01:14:56,583 --> 01:14:58,125
He doesn't remember anything.

1702
01:14:58,208 --> 01:14:59,458
- Nothing.
- (chuckles)

1703
01:14:59,541 --> 01:15:00,375
Oh, no, no.

1704
01:15:00,458 --> 01:15:01,791
(in Italian) <i>Non, non per mio, grazie.</i>

1705
01:15:01,875 --> 01:15:03,666
- No, thank you, Massimo.
- (in Italian) <i>Ciao.</i>

1706
01:15:03,750 --> 01:15:04,625
(in English) Not having anything?

1707
01:15:04,708 --> 01:15:06,750
No, I'm not doing water these days.

1708
01:15:06,833 --> 01:15:08,541
Trying to operate at an aqua deficit.

1709
01:15:08,625 --> 01:15:10,125
- It's poison.
- (Emily) Not poison.

1710
01:15:10,208 --> 01:15:11,791
- (Benji) It is poison.
- So, uh,

1711
01:15:12,916 --> 01:15:14,208
do you think we can pull this off?

1712
01:15:14,291 --> 01:15:15,291
(Benji) Depends on what he's asking.

1713
01:15:15,375 --> 01:15:16,708
- Oh, come on, BB.
- What?

1714
01:15:16,791 --> 01:15:18,458
You can persuade anyone
of anything. You know that.

1715
01:15:18,541 --> 01:15:19,375
Well, that's true.

1716
01:15:19,458 --> 01:15:20,958
I did persuade this one
to go on a date with me.

1717
01:15:21,041 --> 01:15:22,250
To go on a date with you.

1718
01:15:22,333 --> 01:15:23,333
- I know.
- (laughs)

1719
01:15:24,125 --> 01:15:25,750
With all of that ear hair.

1720
01:15:25,833 --> 01:15:27,833
Oh my-- Oh, please.

1721
01:15:27,916 --> 01:15:29,041
It was so awful.

1722
01:15:29,125 --> 01:15:30,750
Andy, if you had seen me
before I met this one.

1723
01:15:30,833 --> 01:15:31,833
I had ear hair.

1724
01:15:31,916 --> 01:15:33,000
(Emily) It was like a jungle in there.

1725
01:15:33,083 --> 01:15:34,000
So much hair growing out of them.

1726
01:15:34,083 --> 01:15:35,083
I had to get him one of the things.

1727
01:15:35,166 --> 01:15:36,958
- The buzzy thing.
- The buzzer. (imitates buzzer)

1728
01:15:37,041 --> 01:15:39,083
Yeah, and then a lawn mower for the rest.

1729
01:15:39,916 --> 01:15:42,125
Can you imagine lawn-mowing my chest?

1730
01:15:42,208 --> 01:15:44,958
I know. I just like him
like a bar of soap.

1731
01:15:45,583 --> 01:15:47,250
That's right, just hairless.

1732
01:15:47,333 --> 01:15:48,333
- (Emily) Oh, there he is.
- Oh.

1733
01:15:48,416 --> 01:15:49,916
What we need to do is get four people on.

1734
01:15:50,000 --> 01:15:51,000
We need to get the accountant,

1735
01:15:51,083 --> 01:15:52,166
we need to get the business manager.

1736
01:15:52,250 --> 01:15:53,458
We need to get everybody's team.

1737
01:15:53,541 --> 01:15:55,166
- Everybody's team.
- Jay!

1738
01:15:55,250 --> 01:15:56,333
Real quick, then.

1739
01:15:56,416 --> 01:15:57,916
You wanna tell me quick?
You can tell me quick.

1740
01:15:58,000 --> 01:15:58,833
(Benji) Jay-Jay!

1741
01:15:58,916 --> 01:16:00,083
You wanna tell me slow,
you can tell me slow.

1742
01:16:00,166 --> 01:16:02,083
- Does he not see us?
- Not at all.

1743
01:16:02,166 --> 01:16:04,166
(bell tolling)

1744
01:16:10,416 --> 01:16:11,416
Oh, there you are.

1745
01:16:11,500 --> 01:16:12,833
- Oh, hi.
- Hi.

1746
01:16:12,916 --> 01:16:14,041
Hey, how was your dinner?

1747
01:16:14,125 --> 01:16:15,833
- Lovely. How was yours?
- Mmm.

1748
01:16:15,916 --> 01:16:17,458
Oh, you know, I just ordered room service.

1749
01:16:17,541 --> 01:16:18,583
- Oh, yeah? Yeah.
- Mm-hmm.

1750
01:16:18,666 --> 01:16:20,333
I love their <i>baccalà mantecato</i> here.

1751
01:16:20,416 --> 01:16:21,875
- Yum. It was so good.
- Yeah.

1752
01:16:21,958 --> 01:16:23,208
Yeah, they don't have that here.

1753
01:16:23,291 --> 01:16:25,250
That's a Venetian dish, not <i>milanese</i>.

1754
01:16:25,333 --> 01:16:26,583
- I...
- Tell me the truth.

1755
01:16:26,666 --> 01:16:28,250
- What's going on?
- What? Nigel.

1756
01:16:28,333 --> 01:16:29,333
You're skulking.

1757
01:16:29,416 --> 01:16:31,500
I know a skulk when I see a skulk.

1758
01:16:31,583 --> 01:16:33,166
- Tell me.
- And... She's here.

1759
01:16:33,250 --> 01:16:36,500
- Morning.
- I can't do this clasp.

1760
01:16:37,000 --> 01:16:38,000
Ready?

1761
01:16:41,458 --> 01:16:44,416
(Nigel) Obviously, security
is going to be very intense.

1762
01:16:44,500 --> 01:16:50,416
And we have hired extensive
<i>protezione </i>for the art.

1763
01:16:54,416 --> 01:16:55,500
(in Italian) <i>Grazie.</i>

1764
01:16:55,583 --> 01:16:56,583
(in English) Okay, everybody.

1765
01:16:56,666 --> 01:17:00,958
I'd like to run through
the dinner for the clients,

1766
01:17:01,666 --> 01:17:02,875
the seating,

1767
01:17:02,958 --> 01:17:05,375
so we have a U-shaped table.

1768
01:17:05,458 --> 01:17:07,000
That's the head up there.

1769
01:17:07,708 --> 01:17:10,000
It's going to end around here someplace,

1770
01:17:10,083 --> 01:17:11,666
about 40 people or more...

1771
01:17:12,375 --> 01:17:13,916
And we're going to take the brands,

1772
01:17:14,000 --> 01:17:15,500
and we're going to mix them up...

1773
01:17:15,583 --> 01:17:17,416
Do you know much about <i>The Last Supper</i>?

1774
01:17:17,500 --> 01:17:18,500
(stammers)

1775
01:17:18,583 --> 01:17:19,833
Not as much as I should.

1776
01:17:20,833 --> 01:17:24,458
Painting this particular scene
was nothing new.

1777
01:17:25,708 --> 01:17:28,791
You can find frescoes
of the same subject matter

1778
01:17:28,875 --> 01:17:29,708
all over Europe,

1779
01:17:29,791 --> 01:17:33,333
but in the other versions,

1780
01:17:33,416 --> 01:17:36,750
the man in charge is
usually depicted with a halo.

1781
01:17:39,791 --> 01:17:43,833
People think that it was
da Vinci's way of saying,

1782
01:17:43,916 --> 01:17:46,916
"We are human. No one is perfect."

1783
01:17:48,208 --> 01:17:52,750
Humans are at once glorious and fallible.

1784
01:17:53,875 --> 01:17:57,750
And inevitably we deceive
and betray one another,

1785
01:17:57,833 --> 01:17:59,750
let each other down.

1786
01:18:00,500 --> 01:18:02,666
(sighs)

1787
01:18:02,750 --> 01:18:05,041
It's what we're built to do.

1788
01:18:09,208 --> 01:18:10,208
Would you agree?

1789
01:18:19,125 --> 01:18:21,125
(♪ tense music plays)

1790
01:18:28,541 --> 01:18:29,833
Okay. Yes.

1791
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:43,166
(laughs)

1792
01:18:43,250 --> 01:18:45,583
What's Andy doing beetling around here?

1793
01:18:46,125 --> 01:18:47,125
(in Italian)<i> Scusa.</i>

1794
01:18:48,708 --> 01:18:50,166
- (in English) Can I help you?
- Miranda knows.

1795
01:18:50,250 --> 01:18:51,458
- What do you mean she knows?
- She knows.

1796
01:18:51,541 --> 01:18:53,708
- How? Did you blab?
- No, but I don't--

1797
01:18:53,791 --> 01:18:55,041
She made it terrifyingly clear to me

1798
01:18:55,125 --> 01:18:56,291
she is aware something is up.

1799
01:18:56,375 --> 01:18:57,541
Oh, for God's sake.

1800
01:18:57,625 --> 01:18:59,125
And I know that we're just
doing this to help her

1801
01:18:59,208 --> 01:19:00,583
but I honestly can't
with the secrets anymore,

1802
01:19:00,666 --> 01:19:02,000
so I think we just...
like, we should tell her.

1803
01:19:02,083 --> 01:19:03,083
- No...
- Yes.

1804
01:19:03,166 --> 01:19:04,916
We will wait until it is done, please.

1805
01:19:05,000 --> 01:19:06,583
(in Italian) Emily, <i>dai</i>

1806
01:19:06,666 --> 01:19:07,583
<i>Mi dai un momento?</i>

1807
01:19:07,666 --> 01:19:09,291
<i>Perché sei sempre</i>
<i>così impaziente, Donatella?</i>

1808
01:19:09,375 --> 01:19:10,416
<i>Per favore!</i>

1809
01:19:10,500 --> 01:19:11,500
(in English) Emily, focus.

1810
01:19:12,625 --> 01:19:13,625
We need to tell Miranda.

1811
01:19:13,708 --> 01:19:15,000
We need to tell her now.

1812
01:19:15,833 --> 01:19:17,500
I feel a little bit sick.

1813
01:19:19,666 --> 01:19:20,833
I'm so nervous I can't breathe.

1814
01:19:20,916 --> 01:19:22,708
- (pants) My neck is hot.
- Oh, my God.

1815
01:19:22,791 --> 01:19:25,083
Just hide a feeling for once, please.

1816
01:19:25,166 --> 01:19:26,416
(knocking on door)

1817
01:19:28,583 --> 01:19:29,416
Oh.

1818
01:19:30,125 --> 01:19:31,000
The Emilys.

1819
01:19:31,083 --> 01:19:32,625
I thought you were Amari.

1820
01:19:32,708 --> 01:19:34,916
Waiting for my Armani.

1821
01:19:35,000 --> 01:19:36,791
Has she been human trafficked?

1822
01:19:37,458 --> 01:19:40,541
Oh. Uh, Jay sprung for the big suite.

1823
01:19:41,166 --> 01:19:42,041
Yeah.

1824
01:19:42,125 --> 01:19:45,333
Well, it's a little snug,
but, you know, I'll manage.

1825
01:19:45,416 --> 01:19:46,833
How can I help you two?

1826
01:19:46,916 --> 01:19:47,916
Um...

1827
01:19:48,416 --> 01:19:50,875
- Okay. Miranda.
- Mm-hmm.

1828
01:19:50,958 --> 01:19:53,041
What Jay wants to do with <i>Runway</i>,

1829
01:19:53,125 --> 01:19:54,291
scaling it so far back that it

1830
01:19:54,375 --> 01:19:56,458
doesn't even resemble what it used to be,

1831
01:19:56,541 --> 01:19:57,875
cutting my department,

1832
01:19:57,958 --> 01:19:59,625
Nigel and most of his department--

1833
01:19:59,708 --> 01:20:01,000
How do you know about that?

1834
01:20:01,083 --> 01:20:04,333
Look, we all know how important

1835
01:20:04,416 --> 01:20:05,875
<i>Runway</i> is and has been.

1836
01:20:05,958 --> 01:20:08,041
Yeah, I mean, <i>Runway</i> is
practically a religion

1837
01:20:08,125 --> 01:20:10,166
and it needs to be protected.

1838
01:20:10,250 --> 01:20:11,916
So I think, you know, the question is,

1839
01:20:12,000 --> 01:20:13,833
who has the means to acquire it?

1840
01:20:13,916 --> 01:20:15,583
Will you two please spit it out already?

1841
01:20:15,666 --> 01:20:16,666
Um... (stammers)

1842
01:20:16,750 --> 01:20:17,750
Benji's buying <i>Runway</i>.

1843
01:20:17,833 --> 01:20:20,208
Benji? Benji Barnes?

1844
01:20:20,291 --> 01:20:22,833
My Benji made Jay Ravitz an offer,

1845
01:20:22,916 --> 01:20:25,708
and Jay readily accepted.

1846
01:20:26,416 --> 01:20:27,875
And you had a part in this?

1847
01:20:27,958 --> 01:20:30,916
Yes, we're doing it
to protect <i>Runway</i> and you.

1848
01:20:31,000 --> 01:20:33,750
You'll be editor-in-chief
for as long as you want to be.

1849
01:20:33,833 --> 01:20:35,541
(stammers) I'm sorry.

1850
01:20:35,625 --> 01:20:39,416
I... I know we've had our differences,

1851
01:20:39,500 --> 01:20:40,666
but I just... I...

1852
01:20:42,041 --> 01:20:43,625
Well, now, I never realized that you

1853
01:20:43,708 --> 01:20:45,458
were capable of this level of betrayal.

1854
01:20:45,541 --> 01:20:47,291
Betrayal? No. Miranda,

1855
01:20:47,375 --> 01:20:49,583
we're preserving <i>Runway</i> for you.

1856
01:20:50,166 --> 01:20:51,000
(Miranda) Oh, no, no, no.

1857
01:20:51,083 --> 01:20:54,250
Miss Emily is not preserving
anything for anybody.

1858
01:20:55,125 --> 01:20:56,291
(stammers) Yes, she is.

1859
01:20:56,375 --> 01:20:57,375
(chuckles) Yes, of course she is.

1860
01:20:57,458 --> 01:20:58,500
Emily.

1861
01:21:01,291 --> 01:21:03,458
Emily, tell her.

1862
01:21:03,541 --> 01:21:05,083
Yeah, Emily.

1863
01:21:05,958 --> 01:21:07,125
Tell her.

1864
01:21:14,583 --> 01:21:16,041
Well, she's right. (sighs)

1865
01:21:19,125 --> 01:21:21,125
Benji's buying <i>Runway</i> for me.

1866
01:21:22,875 --> 01:21:24,125
So that I can run it.

1867
01:21:24,208 --> 01:21:25,708
- What are you talking about?
- (chuckles)

1868
01:21:26,750 --> 01:21:27,875
Look, she's had a long run.

1869
01:21:27,958 --> 01:21:29,333
A historic run.

1870
01:21:30,250 --> 01:21:31,333
But she's exhausted.

1871
01:21:32,000 --> 01:21:35,500
And... And I'm fresher and younger.

1872
01:21:36,958 --> 01:21:39,083
I want to set tastes,
not just cater to them.

1873
01:21:39,166 --> 01:21:40,583
Why would... Why would you do this?

1874
01:21:40,666 --> 01:21:42,166
She knows why.

1875
01:21:42,250 --> 01:21:44,291
(stammers) I have no idea.

1876
01:21:44,375 --> 01:21:46,333
You pushed me out, didn't you?

1877
01:21:46,416 --> 01:21:47,791
I did nothing of the kind.

1878
01:21:47,875 --> 01:21:51,333
You made Dior hire me to get rid of me.

1879
01:21:51,875 --> 01:21:53,958
Why? Why did... Why did you do that?

1880
01:21:54,916 --> 01:21:56,208
(smacks lips, sighs)

1881
01:21:56,291 --> 01:21:57,458
For the same reason

1882
01:21:57,541 --> 01:22:00,625
that you should never
be in charge of <i>Runway</i>, Emily,

1883
01:22:00,708 --> 01:22:03,750
because you are beautiful
and you're intelligent,

1884
01:22:03,833 --> 01:22:05,041
but, no...

1885
01:22:06,833 --> 01:22:08,791
you don't have what it takes.

1886
01:22:10,333 --> 01:22:13,708
I'm sorry, but you're not a visionary.

1887
01:22:15,958 --> 01:22:17,250
You're a vendor.

1888
01:22:18,708 --> 01:22:20,416
You don't know that.

1889
01:22:22,875 --> 01:22:24,291
You don't know the first thing about me.

1890
01:22:24,375 --> 01:22:25,708
You never cared to--

1891
01:22:25,791 --> 01:22:29,916
Oh, I think I do,
and I also think, deep down...

1892
01:22:31,250 --> 01:22:32,250
you know I'm right.

1893
01:22:36,750 --> 01:22:37,750
That's all.

1894
01:22:39,583 --> 01:22:40,833
(breathes shakily)

1895
01:22:43,458 --> 01:22:46,958
Well, Benji's lawyers,
they will be in touch.

1896
01:22:47,833 --> 01:22:49,250
With all the details.

1897
01:22:54,291 --> 01:22:58,458
(stammers) I had no idea.
I'm... I'm so sorry.

1898
01:22:58,541 --> 01:23:00,916
I just felt I had to do something.

1899
01:23:02,208 --> 01:23:04,416
I hope that's not what
you're wearing to the dinner.

1900
01:23:06,458 --> 01:23:07,875
(stammers)

1901
01:23:16,541 --> 01:23:17,958
(sighs)

1902
01:23:20,583 --> 01:23:22,791
(bell tolling)

1903
01:23:26,583 --> 01:23:27,833
(phone buzzes)

1904
01:23:31,875 --> 01:23:33,583
Hey. What's up? How are you?

1905
01:23:33,666 --> 01:23:35,583
Oh, my God, Andy, these pages you sent...

1906
01:23:35,666 --> 01:23:36,750
My boss is freaking out.

1907
01:23:36,833 --> 01:23:38,083
These are perfect.

1908
01:23:38,166 --> 01:23:39,500
Oh. Uh...

1909
01:23:40,041 --> 01:23:41,500
So about that, um, I don't--

1910
01:23:41,583 --> 01:23:43,083
(Talia) <i>There's so much promise here.</i>

1911
01:23:43,166 --> 01:23:45,250
<i>I'm sending you an offer and a contract.</i>

1912
01:23:45,333 --> 01:23:48,000
And, Andy, it's not 50.

1913
01:23:48,083 --> 01:23:49,250
It's not 100.

1914
01:23:49,916 --> 01:23:51,625
It's 350.

1915
01:23:51,708 --> 01:23:53,416
<i>It's three-freaking-fifty.</i>

1916
01:23:56,958 --> 01:23:58,125
- No.
- (Talia) <i>No?</i>

1917
01:23:58,208 --> 01:23:59,208
What do... What do you mean, "no"?

1918
01:23:59,291 --> 01:24:01,333
Don't you mean, like, "hooray"?

1919
01:24:01,416 --> 01:24:02,750
This book,

1920
01:24:02,833 --> 01:24:05,666
it could harm Miranda. I don't...

1921
01:24:05,750 --> 01:24:08,625
(Talia) <i>Which is fine</i>
<i>because she's atrocious.</i>

1922
01:24:09,375 --> 01:24:11,250
It's more complicated than that.

1923
01:24:11,750 --> 01:24:15,541
Okay. Stockholm called.
They want their syndrome back.

1924
01:24:15,625 --> 01:24:18,625
I... (stammers) Can I call you back later?

1925
01:24:18,708 --> 01:24:20,000
Okay. Thanks for letting me know.

1926
01:24:20,083 --> 01:24:21,083
Bye.

1927
01:24:22,666 --> 01:24:24,625
(breathes heavily)

1928
01:24:24,708 --> 01:24:27,750
(Benji laughs) The moon? We've
already been to the moon.

1929
01:24:28,916 --> 01:24:31,041
(Benji) And now, of course,
all the boys wanna go to Mars.

1930
01:24:31,125 --> 01:24:32,041
Fuck Mars.

1931
01:24:32,125 --> 01:24:34,000
Let's go to that big, orange star

1932
01:24:34,083 --> 01:24:35,375
that we call the sun.

1933
01:24:35,458 --> 01:24:36,458
Totally unexplored!

1934
01:24:36,541 --> 01:24:38,083
We've been looking at it for centuries.

1935
01:24:38,166 --> 01:24:39,083
I'm gonna build a little rocket.

1936
01:24:39,166 --> 01:24:40,166
I'm gonna call it <i>The Icarus</i>.

1937
01:24:40,250 --> 01:24:41,750
Icarus did fly too close to the sun.

1938
01:24:41,833 --> 01:24:44,125
- He did fly too close.
- He did. And he fried.

1939
01:24:44,208 --> 01:24:45,875
That's... You're missing the point, honey.

1940
01:24:45,958 --> 01:24:46,875
(Emily) It's like an irony.

1941
01:24:46,958 --> 01:24:48,208
- (Benji) No, it's not ironic.
- What's going on?

1942
01:24:48,291 --> 01:24:49,375
- (Benji) It's...
- Hmm?

1943
01:24:49,458 --> 01:24:51,000
You look like a nervous cat.

1944
01:24:52,291 --> 01:24:53,291
Uh...

1945
01:24:53,791 --> 01:24:55,125
- Compliment?
- No.

1946
01:24:55,208 --> 01:24:57,083
- Hang on a second.
- Oh. Is it... Is it...

1947
01:24:57,166 --> 01:24:58,625
I don't know. I'll go find out.

1948
01:24:58,708 --> 01:24:59,708
So sorry.

1949
01:24:59,791 --> 01:25:01,000
(in Italian) <i>Scusi.</i>

1950
01:25:11,916 --> 01:25:13,750
(in English) I'm ready to make
an announcement.

1951
01:25:13,833 --> 01:25:15,166
Whenever you're ready.

1952
01:25:15,250 --> 01:25:16,458
(Benji) Oh, we're not closed yet.

1953
01:25:16,541 --> 01:25:18,333
Still ironing out some of the details.

1954
01:25:19,000 --> 01:25:20,708
Oh, I see.

1955
01:25:22,208 --> 01:25:23,333
(sighs)

1956
01:25:26,083 --> 01:25:29,666
So generous what you're doing for Emily.

1957
01:25:29,750 --> 01:25:30,750
Oh.

1958
01:25:33,041 --> 01:25:35,583
(chuckles) I know she has many plans.

1959
01:25:36,333 --> 01:25:39,750
But I do hope that some <i>Runway </i>traditions

1960
01:25:39,833 --> 01:25:41,041
are allowed to remain.

1961
01:25:42,166 --> 01:25:43,000
Hmm.

1962
01:25:43,541 --> 01:25:44,583
Who knows?

1963
01:25:45,083 --> 01:25:46,833
Look, the world
is changing so fast sometimes

1964
01:25:46,916 --> 01:25:49,000
that even I can't comprehend it.

1965
01:25:49,083 --> 01:25:50,541
So tradition, well...

1966
01:25:51,208 --> 01:25:53,458
I think a day is coming,
perhaps very soon,

1967
01:25:53,541 --> 01:25:54,791
where, you know,

1968
01:25:54,875 --> 01:25:56,291
<i>Runway</i> won't need models

1969
01:25:56,375 --> 01:25:59,291
or locations or even designers.

1970
01:25:59,375 --> 01:26:01,583
It'll all just, you know, be AI.

1971
01:26:01,666 --> 01:26:03,125
Mmm. Mmm.

1972
01:26:03,208 --> 01:26:07,166
Surely some things will stay the same.

1973
01:26:07,250 --> 01:26:10,833
A commitment to beauty, artistry,

1974
01:26:12,291 --> 01:26:16,875
the best in human achievement, maybe.

1975
01:26:16,958 --> 01:26:17,958
Maybe.

1976
01:26:18,875 --> 01:26:19,875
But...

1977
01:26:22,291 --> 01:26:23,291
look around you.

1978
01:26:25,125 --> 01:26:28,416
We're in an ancient city
that was once part of

1979
01:26:28,500 --> 01:26:31,041
one of the greatest empires
that the world has ever known.

1980
01:26:31,125 --> 01:26:33,833
Now there's just little traces of it left.

1981
01:26:35,583 --> 01:26:37,083
The world is about change.

1982
01:26:37,166 --> 01:26:38,833
That's what human beings don't understand.

1983
01:26:39,583 --> 01:26:41,916
The future just comes
rushing at us like, um...

1984
01:26:42,750 --> 01:26:45,166
well, like the lava of Pompeii.

1985
01:26:47,583 --> 01:26:48,791
Our job is to just let it take

